s-hundreds-of-nate-silvers-re-1830157579 November 1, 2018].\n\n{{ABC News Personalities}}\n{{Sports rating systems}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Silver, Nate}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:ABC News personalities]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American poker players]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American statisticians]]\n[[Category:Baseball statisticians]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Michigan]]\n[[Category:KPMG people]]\n[[Category:LGBT journalists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Michigan]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Online journalists]]\n[[Category:People from East Lansing, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Psephologists]]\n[[Category:The New York Times writers]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Science bloggers]]\n[[Category:ESPN people]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York City]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Data journalism]]\n[[Category:Sportswriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the author and statistician|the American football player|Nate Silver (quarterback)}}\n{{short description|American pundit and writer (born 1978)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| birthname          = Nathaniel Read Silver\n| name               = Nate Silver\n| image              = Nate_Silver_in_Conversation_with_NY1's_Pat_Kiernan_(cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Silver in 2015\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1978|1|13}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/fivethirtyeight/status/21073371737|title=Nate Silver tweet|publisher=Twitter.com|date=August 13, 2010|accessdate=August 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220235453/http://twitter.com/fivethirtyeight/status/21073371737|archive-date=February 20, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[East Lansing, Michigan|East Lansing]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[New York City]]<ref>Eliza Kern, \"How a bad fantasy baseball team turned Nate Silver into America's top data nerd\", [[GigaOM]], [http://gigaom.com/2013/03/10/how-a-bad-fantasy-baseball-team-turned-nate-silver-into-americas-top-data-nerd/ March 10, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515013656/http://gigaom.com/2013/03/10/how-a-bad-fantasy-baseball-team-turned-nate-silver-into-americas-top-data-nerd/ |date=May 15, 2013 }}.</ref>\n| known_for          = [[PECOTA]], ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]''\n| education          = [[University of Chicago]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| employer           = [[ABC News]]\n| occupation         = [[Statistician]], [[journalist]]\n| years_active       = 2000\u2013present\n| title              = Editor in Chief, ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]''\n| website            = {{url|fivethirtyeight.com|FiveThirtyEight.com}}\n}}\n'''Nathaniel Read Silver''' (born January 13, 1978) is an American [[statistician]] and [[writer]] who analyzes [[baseball]] (see [[sabermetrics]]) and elections (see [[psephology]]). He is the founder and editor-in-chief of ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'' and a Special Correspondent for [[ABC News]].\n\nSilver first gained public recognition for developing [[PECOTA]],<ref>[[Alan Schwarz]], \"Numbers Suggest Mets Are Gambling on Zambrano\", [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A05E3DC173EF931A1575BC0A9629C8B63 ''The New York Times'', August 22, 2004] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602124939/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A05E3DC173EF931A1575BC0A9629C8B63 |date=June 2, 2008 }}; [[Alan Schwarz]], \"Predicting Futures in Baseball, and the Downside of Damon\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/13/sports/baseball/13score.html ''The New York Times'', November 13, 2005] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201104027/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/13/sports/baseball/13score.html |date=February 1, 2014 }}; Childs Walker, \"Baseball Prospectus Makes Predicting Future Thing of Past\", ''[[Baltimore Sun]]'', February 21, 2006; Rich Lederer, \"An Unfiltered Interview with Nate Silver\", [http://baseballanalysts.com/archives/2007/02/an_unfiltered_i.php ''Baseball Analysts'', February 12, 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070213001645/http://baseballanalysts.com/archives/2007/02/an_unfiltered_i.php |date=February 13, 2007 }}; Tim Murphy, \"Timeout with Nate Silver: BP's VP illuminates the sport's fuzzy numbers\", [http://www.chicagomaroon.com/2007/5/11/timeout-with-nate-silver-bps-vp-illuminates-the-sports-fuzzy-numbers ''Chicago Maroon'', May 11, 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716141043/http://www.chicagomaroon.com/2007/5/11/timeout-with-nate-silver-bps-vp-illuminates-the-sports-fuzzy-numbers |date=July 16, 2011 }} ; [[Steven Levitt|Steven D. Levitt]], \"Freakonomics: More on Roger Clemens\", [http://freakonomics.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/02/18/more-on-roger-clemens ''The New York Times'', February 18, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219094629/http://freakonomics.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/02/18/more-on-roger-clemens/ |date=February 19, 2008 }}; and Michael Miner, \"The Algorithm Method: Hot Type's coveted Golden BAT award goes to a computer program\", [http://www.chicagoreader.com/features/stories/hottype/080327 ''[[Chicago Reader]]'', March 27, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406025920/http://www.chicagoreader.com/features/stories/hottype/080327/ |date=April 6, 2008 }}.</ref> a system for forecasting the performance and career development of [[Major League Baseball]] players, which he sold to and then managed for [[Baseball Prospectus]] from 2003 to 2009.<ref name=\"baseballprospectus1\">\nNate Silver and Kevin Goldstein, \"State of the Prospectus: Spring 2009\", [http://baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=8653 ''BaseballProspectus.com,'' March 24, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327063757/http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=8653 |date=March 27, 2009 }} \n</ref>\n\nSilver was named one of [[Time 100|The World's 100 Most Influential People]] by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' in 2009 after an election forecasting system he developed successfully predicted the outcomes in 49 of the 50 states in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 U.S. Presidential election]].<ref name=\"specials1\">{{cite magazine|last=Stein|first=Joel|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/0,28757,1894410,00.html|title=The World's Most Influential People \u2013 The 2009 TIME 100|magazine=TIME|accessdate=May 8, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508170110/http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/0,28757,1894410,00.html|archive-date=May 8, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2012 United States presidential election]], the forecasting system correctly predicted the winner of all 50 states and the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]].<ref name=\"TelegraphNate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/us-election/9662363/Nate-Silver-politics-geek-hailed-for-Barack-Obama-wins-US-election-forecast.html|title=Nate Silver: politics 'geek' hailed for Barack Obama wins US election forecast|publisher=The Telegragh|date=November 7, 2012|accessdate=November 8, 2012|author=Hough, Andrew|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108102807/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/us-election/9662363/Nate-Silver-politics-geek-hailed-for-Barack-Obama-wins-US-election-forecast.html|archive-date=November 8, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the ''FiveThirtyEight'' blog was licensed for publication by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"FiveThirtyEight.com, June 3, 2010\">Nate Silver, \"FiveThirtyEight to Partner with New York Times\", [http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2010/06/fivethirtyeight-to-partner-with-new.html FiveThirtyEight.com, June 3, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606173921/http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2010/06/fivethirtyeight-to-partner-with-new.html |date=June 6, 2010 }}.</ref><ref>[[Brian Stelter]], \"Times to Host Blog on Politics and Polls\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/04/business/media/04silver.html ''The New York Times'', June 3, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229071308/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/04/business/media/04silver.html |date=December 29, 2016 }}.</ref> In 2012 and 2013, ''FiveThirtyEight'' won [[Webby Award]]s as the \"Best Political Blog\" from the [[International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences]].\n\nIn July 2013, Silver sold ''FiveThirtyEight'' to ESPN, and Silver became its Editor in Chief.<ref>Brian Stelter, \"Nate Silver of FiveThirtyEight Blog Is to Join ESPN Staff\", ''The New York Times'', [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/20/business/media/nate-silver-blogger-for-new-york-times-is-to-join-espn-staff.html July 19, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415062133/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/20/business/media/nate-silver-blogger-for-new-york-times-is-to-join-espn-staff.html |date=April 15, 2017 }}.</ref> The ESPN-owned ''FiveThirtyEight'' launched on March 17, 2014. The site focused on a broad range of subjects under the rubric of \"[[data journalism]]\".<ref name=\"March 17, 2014\">Nate Silver, \"What the Fox Knows\", ''FiveThirtyEight,'' [http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/what-the-fox-knows/ March 17, 2014] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317174126/http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/what-the-fox-knows/ |date=March 17, 2014 }}.</ref>\n\nSilver's book, ''[[The Signal and the Noise]]'', was published in September 2012. It subsequently reached [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' best seller list]] for nonfiction, and was named by [[Amazon.com]] as the No. 1 best nonfiction book of 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/b/ref=sr_aj?node=5917235011&ajr=0 |title=Amazon No. 1 of 2012 |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20121210032533/http://www.amazon.com/books-used-books-textbooks/b?ie=UTF8&node=283155 |archive-date=December 10, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Signal and the Noise'' won the 2013 [[Phi Beta Kappa Award in Science]].<ref name=\"pbk.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pbk.org/home/newsview.aspx?id=998 |title=Phi Beta Kappa book award in science |publisher=Pbk.org |date=October 8, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024041741/http://www.pbk.org/home/newsview.aspx?id=998 |archive-date=October 24, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The book has been translated into eleven languages: Chinese (separate editions in traditional and simplified characters), Czech, Finnish, German, Italian, Polish, Portuguese, Romanian, Russian, and Spanish.\n\nHaving earned a bachelor's degree from [[The University of Chicago]] in 2000, Silver has since been awarded six honorary doctoral degrees: from [[Ripon College (Wisconsin)|Ripon College]] (2013), [[The New School]] (2013), The [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven|University of Leuven]] (2013), [[Amherst College]] (2014), [[Georgetown University]] (2017), and [[Kenyon College]] (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nSilver was born in [[East Lansing, Michigan]], the son of Sally (n\u00e9e Thrun), a community activist, and Brian David Silver, a former chair of the [[political science]] department at [[Michigan State University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/lansingstatejournal/access/1701930301.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+05%2C+2008&author=Derek+Wallbank&pub=Lansing+State+Journal&desc=E.L.+native's+predictions+pitch+politics+a+curveball&pqatl=google|title=Wallbank, '&#39;Lansing State Journal'&#39;|publisher=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com|date=July 5, 2008|accessdate=August 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725065922/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/lansingstatejournal/access/1701930301.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+05%2C+2008&author=Derek+Wallbank&pub=Lansing+State+Journal&desc=E.L.+native's+predictions+pitch+politics+a+curveball&pqatl=google|archive-date=July 25, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SI-VqAT4_hYC&pg=PT474&lpg=PT474&dq=Sally+Thrun+Silver&source=bl&ots=7nKOV7bgJI&sig=0RRuzd5T9IaNxpYdV4I6atPNafU&hl=en |title=The Signal and the Noise: Why So Many Predictions Fail-but Some Don't - Nate Silver - Google Books |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629122921/https://books.google.com/books?id=SI-VqAT4_hYC&pg=PT474&lpg=PT474&dq=Sally+Thrun+Silver&source=bl&ots=7nKOV7bgJI&sig=0RRuzd5T9IaNxpYdV4I6atPNafU&hl=en |archive-date=June 29, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Silver's mother's family, of English and German descent, includes several distinguished men and women, including his maternal great-grandfather, Harmon Lewis, who was president of the Alcoa Steamship Company, Inc.<ref name=intfi1>{{cite news|last=Bloom|first=Nate|url=http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/Interfaith_Celebrities_Nate_Silver_Another_Bond_and_Happy_Endings.shtml|title=Interfaithfamily|publisher=Interfaithfamily|accessdate=December 5, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827002622/http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/Interfaith_Celebrities_Nate_Silver_Another_Bond_and_Happy_Endings.shtml|archive-date=August 27, 2014|url-status=live}} This source also gives the origin of Silver's middle name, Read, which was shared by his mother's mother and sister. Silver has a namesake, \"Nathaniel Read\" in the family line that dates from the early 18th century.</ref> Silver has described himself as \"[[half-Jewish]]\".<ref name=intfi1/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1012/82071.html |title=Answer This: Nate Silver - Patrick Gavin |publisher=Politico.Com |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329101425/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1012/82071.html |archive-date=March 29, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSilver showed a proficiency in math from a young age.<ref>Stephanie Clifford, \"Finding Fame With a Prescient Call for Obama\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/10/business/media/10silver.html ''The New York Times'', November 9, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224063509/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/10/business/media/10silver.html |date=February 24, 2015 }}.</ref> According to journalist William Hageman, \"Silver caught the baseball bug when he was 6.... It was 1984, the year the [[Detroit Tigers]] won the [[World Series]]. The Tigers became his team and baseball his sport. And if there's anything that goes hand in glove with baseball, it's numbers, another of Silver's childhood interests (\"It's always more interesting to apply it to batting averages than algebra class\").<ref>William Hageman, \"Baseball by the Numbers\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' (January 4, 2006).</ref>\n\nAs a student at [[East Lansing High School]], in 1996 Silver won first place in the State of [[Michigan]] in the 49th annual [[John S. Knight]] Scholarship Contest for senior high school debaters.<ref>\"East Lansing Debater Wins Scholarship\", ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' (February 29, 1996). Also see Patricia Montemurri, \"Michigan native Nate Silver shows election predictions aren't magic but math\", [http://www.freep.com/article/20121111/NEWS15/311110221/Michigan-native-Nate-Silver-shows-election-predictions-aren-t-magic-but-math?odyssey=tab|topnews|text|FRONTPAGE ''Detroit Free Press'', November 11, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924113619/http://www.freep.com/article/20121111/NEWS15/311110221/Michigan-native-Nate-Silver-shows-election-predictions-aren-t-magic-but-math?odyssey=tab%7Ctopnews%7Ctext%7CFRONTPAGE |date=September 24, 2015 }}.</ref>\n\nSilver first showed his [[journalism]] skills as a writer and opinion page editor for ''The Portrait'', East Lansing High School's student newspaper, from 1993\u20131996.<ref>\n[http://www.redeyechicago.com/news/redeye-drunk-nate-silver-heres-a-yearbook-photo-before-he-could-drink-20121108,0,6368696.story Link to 1996 high school yearbook photo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108195645/http://www.redeyechicago.com/news/redeye-drunk-nate-silver-heres-a-yearbook-photo-before-he-could-drink-20121108,0,6368696.story |date=November 8, 2012 }}  with brief resume showing status as writer for ''The Portrait'' for three years and editor for two years. [retrieved November 8, 2012]\n</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Silver graduated with Honors with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[economics]] from the [[University of Chicago]]. He also wrote for the ''[[Chicago Weekly|Chicago Weekly News]]'' and the ''[[Chicago Maroon]]''. He spent his third year at the [[London School of Economics]].<ref>Nate Silver, \"Random, Pretentious Observations from Europe\", [http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2009/05/random-pretentious-observations-from.html ''FiveThirtyEight.com,'' May 25, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528075838/http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2009/05/random-pretentious-observations-from.html |date=May 28, 2009 }}.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Economic consultant: 2000\u20132003===\nAfter college graduation in 2000, Silver worked for three and a half years as a [[transfer pricing]] consultant with [[KPMG]] in [[Chicago]]. When asked in 2009, \"What is your biggest regret in life?\" Silver responded, \"Spending four years of my life at a job I didn't like\".<ref>Stephen J. Dubner, \"FREAK-Quently Asked Questions: Nate Silver\", [http://freakonomics.com/2009/03/12/freak-quently-asked-questions-nate-silver/ ''freakonomics.com'', March 12, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817161451/http://freakonomics.com/2009/03/12/freak-quently-asked-questions-nate-silver/ |date=August 17, 2018 }}.</ref> While employed at KPMG, Silver continued to nurture his lifelong interest in baseball and statistics, and on the side he began to work on his [[PECOTA]] system for projecting player performance and careers. He quit his job at KPMG in April 2004 and for a time earned his living mainly by playing [[online poker]].<ref>Rob Kaiser, \"Players Place Bets on Poker as Career\", [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-10-03/business/0410030372_1_online-poker-poker-sites-interest-in-online-gaming ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', October 3, 2004] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115164158/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-10-03/business/0410030372_1_online-poker-poker-sites-interest-in-online-gaming |date=January 15, 2013 }}. According to ''Sports Illustrated'' writer [[Alexander Wolff]], over a three-year period Silver earned $400,000 from online poker. See Alexander Wolff, \"Scorecard: He's ''So'' Predictable\", [http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1205991/index.htm ''Sports Illustrated,'' September 17, 2012, p. 15] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026023924/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1205991/index.htm |date=October 26, 2012 }}.</ref>\n\n===Baseball analyst: 2003\u20132008===\nIn 2003, Silver became a writer for ''[[Baseball Prospectus]]'' (BP), after having sold PECOTA to BP in return for a partnership interest. After resigning from KPMG in 2004, he took the position of Executive Vice-President, later renamed Managing Partner of BP. Silver further developed PECOTA and wrote a weekly column under the heading \"Lies, Damned Lies\". He applied [[sabermetric]] techniques to a broad range of topics including forecasting the performance of individual players, the economics of baseball, metrics for the [[valuation (finance)|valuation]] of players, and developing an [[Elo rating system]] for Major League baseball.<ref>Nate Silver, \"We are Elo?\", [http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=5247 ''BaseballProspectus.com'' (June 28, 2006)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206112913/http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=5247 |date=February 6, 2007 }} and Nate Silver, \"More on Elo\", [http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=5271 ''BaseballProspectus.com'' (July 5, 2006)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210031318/http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=5271 |date=February 10, 2007 }}.</ref>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2009, Silver co-authored the ''Baseball Prospectus'' annual book of [[Major League Baseball]] forecasts,<ref>''Baseball Prospectus'' ({{isbn|0-7611-3995-8}})</ref> as well as other books, including ''Mind Game: How the Boston Red Sox Got Smart, Won a World Series, and Created a New Blueprint for Winning'',<ref>''Mind Game: How the Boston Red Sox Got Smart, Won a World Series, and Created a New Blueprint for Winning'' (New York: Workman Publishers, 2005) ({{isbn|0-7611-4018-2}})</ref> ''Baseball Between the Numbers'',<ref>''Baseball Between the Numbers'' (New York: Basic Books, 2006) ({{isbn|0-465-00596-9}})</ref> and ''It Ain't Over 'til It's Over: The Baseball Prospectus Pennant Race Book''.<ref>''It Ain't Over 'til It's Over: The Baseball Prospectus Pennant Race Book'' (New York: Basic Books, 2007) ({{isbn|0-465-00284-6}})</ref>\n\nHe contributed articles about baseball to [[ESPN.com]], ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', the ''[[New York Sun]]'', and ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>Nate Silver, \"For Griffey, the Roads Not Taken\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/11/sports/baseball/11score.html ''The New York Times'', May 11, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802054248/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/11/sports/baseball/11score.html |date=August 2, 2017 }}.</ref>\n\nSilver has authored more than 200 articles for Baseball Prospectus.<ref>See [http://www.baseballprospectus.com/news/?author=59 Nate Silver's ''Baseball Prospectus'' article archive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912144035/http://www.baseballprospectus.com/news/?author=59 |date=September 12, 2011 }} (2003\u20132009)</ref>\n\n====PECOTA====\n{{Main|PECOTA}}\nPECOTA (Player Empirical Comparison and Optimization Test Algorithm) is a statistical system that projects the future performance of hitters and pitchers. It is designed primarily for two uses: fans interested in [[fantasy baseball]], and professionals in the baseball business trying to predict the performance and [[valuation (finance)|valuation]] of major league players. Unlike most other baseball projection systems, PECOTA relies on matching a given current player to a set of \"comparable\" players whose past performance can serve as a guide to how the given current player is likely to perform in the future. Unlike most other such systems, PECOTA also calculates a range of probable performance levels rather than a single predicted value on a given measure such as [[earned run average]] or [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]].\n\nPECOTA projections were first published by [[Baseball Prospectus]] in the 2003 edition of its annual book as well as online by ''BaseballProspectus.com.'' Silver produced the PECOTA forecasts for each [[Major League Baseball]] season from 2003 through 2009.<ref name=\"baseballprospectus1\"/>\n\n==Political analyst and blogger: 2008\u2013present==\n\n===''FiveThirtyEight'' blog===\n{{Main|FiveThirtyEight}}\n[[File:Nate_Silver_2009.png|thumb|Silver at [[South by Southwest|SXSW]] in 2009]]\n\n====Creation and motivation====\nOn November 1, 2007, while still employed by Baseball Prospectus, Silver began publishing a diary under the pseudonym \"Poblano\" on the progressive political blog ''[[Daily Kos]].''<ref>The first diary was titled, \"HRC [Hillary Roddam Clinton] Electability in Purple States, [http://www.dailykos.com/story/2007/11/01/405019/-HRC-Electability-in-Purple-States ''DailyKos'', November 1, 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028010032/http://www.dailykos.com/story/2007/11/01/405019/-HRC-Electability-in-Purple-States |date=October 28, 2012 }}.</ref> Silver set out to analyze quantitative aspects of the political game to enlighten a broader audience. Silver reports that \"he was stranded in a New Orleans airport when the idea of ''FiveThirtyEight.com'' came to him. 'I was just frustrated with the analysis. ... I saw a lot of discussion about strategy that was not all that sophisticated, especially when it came to quantitative things like polls and demographics'\".<ref>Hannah Hayes, \"What Will Nate Silver Do Next?\", [https://www.uchicago.edu/features/20090126_silver.shtml University of Chicago (webpage feature story), January, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606102224/http://www.uchicago.edu/features/20090126_silver.shtml |date=June 6, 2011 }}.</ref> His forecasts of the 2008 [[United States presidential primary]] elections drew a lot of attention, including being cited by ''[[The New York Times]]'' Op-Ed columnist [[William Kristol]].<ref>William Kristol, \"Obama's Path to Victory\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/11/opinion/11kristol.html ''The New York Times'', February 11, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229070940/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/11/opinion/11kristol.html |date=December 29, 2016 }}.</ref>\n\nOn March 7, 2008, while still writing as \"Poblano\", Silver established his own blog, ''[[FiveThirtyEight.com]]''. Often colloquially referred to as just 538, the website takes its name from the number of electors in the United States [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral college]].<ref name=\"faq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2008/03/frequently-asked-questions-last-revised.html|title=Frequently Asked Questions|last=Silver|first=Nate|work=FiveThirtyEight.com|accessdate=November 4, 2008|date=August 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227173932/http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2008/03/frequently-asked-questions-last-revised.html|archive-date=February 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2008, Poblano revealed his identity to ''FiveThirtyEight.com'' readers.<ref>Nate Silver, \"No I'm Not [[Chuck Todd]]\", [http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2008/05/no-im-not-chuck-todd.html ''FiveThirtyEight.com,'' May 30, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204075532/http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2008/05/no-im-not-chuck-todd.html |date=December 4, 2008 }}.</ref> On June 1, 2008, Silver published a two-page Op-Ed article in the ''[[New York Post]]'' outlining the rationale underlying his focus on the statistical aspects of politics.<ref>Nate Silver, \"Margins of Error\", [http://www.nypost.com/seven/06012008/postopinion/opedcolumnists/margins_of_error_113360.htm ''[[New York Post]],'' June 1, 2008.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910203021/http://www.nypost.com/seven/06012008/postopinion/opedcolumnists/margins_of_error_113360.htm |date=September 10, 2008 }}</ref> He first appeared on national television on [[CNN]]'s ''[[American Morning]]'' on June 13, 2008.<ref>Nate Silver, \"CNN Video\", [http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2008/06/cnn-video.html FiveThirtyEight.com, June 13, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616201911/http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2008/06/cnn-video.html |date=June 16, 2008 }}.</ref>\n\nSilver described his partisan orientation as follows in the [[FAQ]] on his website: \"My state [Illinois] has non-partisan registration, so I am not registered as anything. I vote for Democratic candidates the majority of the time (though by no means always). This year, I have been a supporter of Barack Obama\".<ref name=\"FiveThirtyEight.com\">Nate Silver, \"Frequently Asked Questions, Last Revised 8/7/08\", [http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2008/03/frequently-asked-questions-last-revised.html ''FiveThirtyEight.com''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227173932/http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2008/03/frequently-asked-questions-last-revised.html |date=February 27, 2014 }}</ref> With respect to the impartiality of his electoral projections, Silver stated, \"Are [my] results biased toward [my] preferred candidates? I hope not, but that is for you to decide. I have tried to disclose as much about my methodology as possible\".<ref name=\"FiveThirtyEight.com\"/>\n\n====2008 election and aftermath====\nShortly after the November 4 election, [[ESPN]] writer [[Jim Caple]] observed, \"Forget [[Cole Hamels]] and the [[Phillies]]. No one in baseball had a more impressive fall than Nate Silver....  [R]ight now Silver is exhausted. He barely slept the last couple weeks of the campaign\u2014'By the end, it was full-time plus'\u2014and for that matter, he says he couldn't have kept it up had the campaign lasted two days longer. Plus, he has his Baseball Prospectus duties. 'We write our [''Baseball Prospectus 2009''] book from now through the first of the year,' [Silver] said. 'I have a week to relax and then it gets just as busy again. In February 2009 I will just have to find an island in the Caribbean and throw my [[BlackBerry]] in the ocean'\".<ref>[[Jim Caple]], \"In baseball, and in politics, the numbers don't lie\", \"Page 2\", [http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=caple/081107 ''[[ESPN.com]],'' November 7, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222123417/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=caple%2F081107 |date=December 22, 2015 }}.</ref>\n\nLater in November 2008, Silver signed a contract with [[Penguin Books|Penguin Group USA]] to write two books, reportedly for a $700,000 advance.<ref>Leon Neyfakh, \"Nate Silver Signs With Penguin In Two Book Deal Worth About $700,000\", [http://www.observer.com/2008/media/nate-silver-signs-penguin-two-book-deal-worth-sum-high-six-figures ''New York Observer,'' November 14, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202033617/http://www.observer.com/2008/media/nate-silver-signs-penguin-two-book-deal-worth-sum-high-six-figures |date=December 2, 2008 }}.</ref>\n\nSilver was invited to be a speaker at [[TED (conference)|TED 2009]] in February 2009,<ref>See [http://conferences.ted.com/TED2009/program/ TED2009 program] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081226232833/http://conferences.ted.com/TED2009/program/ |date=December 26, 2008 }} and Shanna Carpenter, \"Race and the City: An Exclusive Interview with Nate Silver\", [http://blog.ted.com/2009/04/race_and_the_ci.php TED Blog, April 29, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430154127/http://blog.ted.com/2009/04/race_and_the_ci.php |date=April 30, 2009 }}.</ref> and keynote speaker at the 2009 [[South by Southwest]] (SXSW) Interactive conference (March 2009).<ref>[[Daniel Terdiman]], \"[http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-10196750-38.html FiveThirtyEight.com's Nate Silver on life post-election] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207212530/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-10196750-38.html |date=February 7, 2012 }}\", [[CNET.com]], March 15, 2009, and Dan Fost, \"[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2009/03/nate-silver-sxs.html SXSW: Statistics guru Nate Silver talks Oscars, Manny Ramirez and President Obama] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090322122807/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2009/03/nate-silver-sxs.html |date=March 22, 2009 }}\",  ''Los Angeles Times'', March 16, 2009. See [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KOVM4SIQdmo Video of SXSW Keynote Interview, part 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201031658/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KOVM4SIQdmo |date=February 1, 2017 }} and [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FygQVyO4lyE part 2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201031702/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FygQVyO4lyE |date=February 1, 2017 }}.</ref>\n\nWhile maintaining his ''FiveThirtyEight.com'' website, in January 2009 Silver began a monthly feature column, \"The Data\", in ''[[Esquire Magazine|Esquire]]''<ref>{{cite web |last=Silver |first=Nate |url=http://www.esquire.com/archive/features/data/0/10/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729061021/http://www.esquire.com/archive/features/data/0/10/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 29, 2012 |title=The Data |publisher=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |accessdate=May 8, 2009 }}</ref> as well as contributed occasional articles to other media such as ''The New York Times''<ref>Nate Silver and [[Andrew Gelman]], \"No Country for Close Calls\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/19/opinion/19silver.html ''The New York Times'', April 18, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802053234/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/19/opinion/19silver.html |date=August 2, 2017 }}.</ref> and ''The Wall Street Journal''.<ref>Nate Silver, \"Crunching the Risk Numbers\", [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703481004574646963713065116 ''The Wall Street Journal'', January 8, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171124170340/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703481004574646963713065116 |date=November 24, 2017 }}.</ref>  He also tried his luck in the [[2009 World Series of Poker]].<ref>Nate Silver, \"This Post Brought to You By Poker\", [http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2009/07/this-post-brought-to-you-by-poker.html#comments ''FiveThirtyEight.com,'' July 2, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704190530/http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2009/07/this-post-brought-to-you-by-poker.html#comments |date=July 4, 2009 }}.</ref>\n\nThe success of his ''FiveThirtyEight.com'' blog marked the effective end of Silver's career as baseball analyst, though he continued to devote some attention to sports statistics and sports economics in his blog. In March 2009, he stepped down as Managing Partner of Baseball Prospectus and handed over responsibility for producing future PECOTA projections to other Baseball Prospectus staff members.<ref name=\"baseballprospectus1\"/> In April 2009, he appeared as an analyst on ESPN's ''[[Baseball Tonight]]''. After March 2009, he published only two \"Lies, Damned Lies\" columns on ''BaseballProspectus.com.''\n\nIn November 2009, ESPN introduced a new Soccer Power Index (SPi),<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/spi/rankings ESPN's SPi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121041821/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/spi/rankings |date=January 21, 2012 }}.</ref> designed by Nate Silver, for predicting the outcome of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>Nate Silver, \"The Purpose of the Soccer Power Index\", [http://espn.go.com/soccer/worldcup/news/_/id/4537460/purpose-spi ESPN.com, November 11, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091114153249/http://espn.go.com/soccer/worldcup/news/_/id/4537460/purpose-spi |date=November 14, 2009 }} and Nate Silver, \"A Guide to ESPN's SPI Ratings\", [http://espn.go.com/soccer/worldcup/news/_/id/4447078/guide-espn-spi-ratings ''ESPN.com,'' November 11, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119065602/http://espn.go.com/soccer/worldcup/news/_/id/4447078/guide-espn-spi-ratings |date=November 19, 2009 }}. For a comment see Carl Bialik, \"ESPN's New Soccer Rankings\", [https://blogs.wsj.com/dailyfix/2009/11/11/the-count-espns-new-soccer-rankings/ ''The Wall Street Journal'', November 11, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303165350/http://blogs.wsj.com/dailyfix/2009/11/11/the-count-espns-new-soccer-rankings/ |date=March 3, 2016 }}.</ref> He published a post-mortem after the tournament, comparing his predictions to those of alternative rating systems.<ref>Nate Silver, \"SPI in review: How did it do?\", [http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/columns/story/_/id/5392992/ce/us/soccer-power-index-update?cc=5901&ver=us ''ESPN.com,'' July 19, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128160929/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/columns/story/_/id/5392992/ce/us/soccer-power-index-update?cc=5901&ver=us |date=January 28, 2012 }} [Retrieved July 21, 2010].</ref>\n\nIn April 2010, in an assignment for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, Silver created a quantitative index of \"The Most Livable Neighborhoods in New York\".<ref>Nate Silver, \"The Most Livable Neighborhoods in New York: a quantitative index of the 50 most satisfying places to live\", [http://nymag.com/realestate/neighborhoods/2010/65374/ ''[[New York Magazine]],'' April 11, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6AHFef84k?url=http://nymag.com/realestate/neighborhoods/2010/65374/ |date=August 29, 2012 }}.</ref>\n\n====Transition to ''The New York Times''====\nOn June 3, 2010, Silver announced on ''FiveThirtyEight.com,''\n\n<blockquote>In the near future, the blog will \"re-launch\" under a NYTimes.com domain. It will retain its own identity (akin to other Times blogs like [[DealBook]]), but will be organized under the News:Politics section. Once this occurs, content will no longer be posted at ''FiveThirtyEight.com'' on an ongoing basis, and the blog will re-direct to the new [[URL]]. In addition, I will be contributing content to the print edition of ''The New York Times'', and to the ''Sunday Magazine''. The partnership agreement, which is structured as a license, has a term of three years.<ref name=\"FiveThirtyEight.com, June 3, 2010\"/><ref>For more information about the working agreement between ''The Times'' and Nate Silver's blog, see Mallory Jean Tenore, \"FiveThirtyEight's Nate Silver adjusts to New York Times, 6 months after joining the newsroom\", [http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/top-stories/120212/fivethirtyeights-nate-silver-adjusts-to-new-york-times-as-a-blogger-6-months-after-joining-the-newsroom/ ''Poynter,'' June 3, 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225020129/http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/top-stories/120212/fivethirtyeights-nate-silver-adjusts-to-new-york-times-as-a-blogger-6-months-after-joining-the-newsroom/ |date=February 25, 2011 }} , and Margaret Sullivan, \"On Identifying a Rape Victim, Naming a Prophet, and Nate Silver's Role\", [http://publiceditor.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/21/on-identifying-a-rape-victim-naming-a-prophet-and-nate-silvers-role-the-public-editor/ ''The New York Times'', September 21, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120924061651/http://publiceditor.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/21/on-identifying-a-rape-victim-naming-a-prophet-and-nate-silvers-role-the-public-editor/ |date=September 24, 2012 }}.</ref></blockquote>\n\n''The New York Times'' \"FiveThirtyEight: Nate Silver's Political Calculus\" commenced on August 25, 2010, with the publication of \"New Forecast Shows Democrats Losing 6 to 7 Senate Seats\".<ref>Nate Silver, \"New Forecast Shows Democrats Losing 6 to 7 Senate Seats\", [http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/25/new-forecast-shows-democrats-losing-6-to-7-senate-seats/ FiveThirtyEight/NYT, August 25, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213005055/http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/25/new-forecast-shows-democrats-losing-6-to-7-senate-seats/ |date=December 13, 2014 }}.</ref> From that date the blog focused almost exclusively on forecasting the outcomes of the 2010 [[United States Senate elections, 2010|U.S. Senate]] and [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2010|U.S. House of Representatives]] elections as well as [[United States gubernatorial elections, 2010|state gubernatorial]] contests. Silver's ''Times Sunday Magazine'' feature first appeared on November 19, 2010, under the heading \"Go Figure\".<ref>Nate Silver, \"Go Figure: Who's No. 1?\" [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/21/magazine/21fob-gofigure-t.html NY Times Magazine, November 19, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802053119/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/21/magazine/21fob-gofigure-t.html |date=August 2, 2017 }}.</ref> It was later titled \"Acts of Mild Subversion\".<ref>For example, Nate Silver, \"How to Beat the Salad Bar\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/20/magazine/mag-20Subversion-t.html ''The New York Times'', March 17, 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117091123/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/20/magazine/mag-20Subversion-t.html |date=January 17, 2017 }}.</ref>\n\nWhile blogging for ''The Times,'' Silver also worked on his book about prediction, which was published in September 2012. At that time, Silver began to drop hints that after 2012 he would turn his attention to matters other than detailed statistical forecasting of elections. As reported in ''New York'' magazine: \" 'I view my role now as providing more of a macro-level skepticism, rather than saying this poll is good or this poll is evil,' he says. And in four [years], he might be even more macro, as he turns his forecasting talents to other fields. 'I'm 97 percent sure that the FiveThirtyEight model will exist in 2016,' he says, 'but it could be someone else who's running it or licensing it.'\"<ref>Jason Zengerle, \"The. Polls. Have. Stopped. Making. Any. Sense.\", [http://nymag.com/news/features/election-polls-2012-10/ ''New York,'' September 30. 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001221732/http://nymag.com/news/features/election-polls-2012-10/ |date=October 1, 2012 }}.</ref>\n\nDuring the last year of ''FiveThirtyEight''{{'}}s license to ''The Times,'' it drew a very large volume of [[web traffic|online traffic]] to the paper:\n\n<blockquote>The Times does not release traffic figures, but a spokesperson said yesterday that Silver's blog provided a significant\u2014and significantly growing, over the past year\u2014percentage of Times pageviews. This fall, visits to the Times' political coverage (including FiveThirtyEight) have increased, both absolutely and as a percentage of site visits. But FiveThirtyEight's growth is staggering: where earlier this year, somewhere between 10 and 20 percent of politics visits included a stop at FiveThirtyEight, last week that figure was 71 percent.</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>But Silver's blog has buoyed more than just the politics coverage, becoming a significant traffic-driver for the site as a whole. Earlier this year, approximately 1 percent of visits to the New York Times included ''FiveThirtyEight.'' Last week, that number was 13 percent. Yesterday, it was 20 percent. That is, one in five visitors to the sixth-most-trafficked U.S. news site took a look at Silver's blog.<ref>Marc Tracy, \"Nate Silver Is a One-Man Traffic Machine for the Times\", ''[[The New Republic]]'', November 6, 2012.</ref></blockquote>\n\n=====Departure from ''The Times''=====\n[[File:Nate Silver on Employee of the Month with Catie Lazarus, December 2015.webm|thumb|Silver on leaving ''The New York Times'']]\nIn an online chat session a week after the 2012 election Silver commented: \"As tempting as it might be to pull a [[Jim Brown]]/[[Sandy Koufax]] and just [[Mic drop|mic-drop]]/retire from elections forecasting, I expect that we'll be making forecasts in 2014 and 2016. Midterm elections can be dreadfully boring, unfortunately. But the 2016 [[Republican Party (United States)|G.O.P.]] primary seems almost certain to be epic.\"<ref>\"Skew Yourselves: Nate Silver Is Here To Answer Your Questions\", [http://deadspin.com/5960364/skew-yourselves-nate-silver-is-here-to-answer-your-questions ''[[Deadspin]],'' November 14, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117092802/http://deadspin.com/5960364/skew-yourselves-nate-silver-is-here-to-answer-your-questions |date=November 17, 2012 }}.</ref> In late November 2012, ''Times'' executive editor [[Jill Abramson]] declared her wish to keep Silver and his blog: \"We would love to have Nate continue to be part of the New York Times family, and to expand on what he does\", she said. \"We know he began in sports anyway, so it is not an exclusively political product. I am excited to talk to Nate when he finishes his book tour about ways to expand that kind of reporting.\"<ref>Alex Weprin, \"The New York Times Wants To Keep Nate Silver, 'Expand On What He Does'\", ''[[Mediabistro.com|Mediabistro]],'' [http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlny/the-new-york-times-wants-to-keep-nate-silver-expand-on-what-he-does_b72049 November 27, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121129235733/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlny/the-new-york-times-wants-to-keep-nate-silver-expand-on-what-he-does_b72049 |date=November 29, 2012 }}. Also see Connor Simpson, \"What the Future Holds for Nate Silver at The New York Times\", ''[[The Atlantic|Atlantic Wire]],'' [http://www.theatlanticwire.com/business/2012/11/what-future-holds-nate-silver-and-new-york-times/59369/ November 27, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121129171448/http://www.theatlanticwire.com/business/2012/11/what-future-holds-nate-silver-and-new-york-times/59369/ |date=November 29, 2012 }}.</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2013, ESPN announced that it had acquired ownership of the ''FiveThirtyEight'' website and brand, and that \"Silver will serve as editor-in-chief of the site and will build a team of journalists, editors, analysts and contributors in the coming months.\"<ref>\"Nate Silver makes move to ESPN\", [[ESPN.com]], [http://espn.go.com/espn/story/_/id/9499752/nate-silver-joins-espn-multifaceted-role July 22, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725054022/http://espn.go.com/espn/story/_/id/9499752/nate-silver-joins-espn-multifaceted-role |date=July 25, 2013 }}; \"Nate Silver \u2013 Renowned Statistician, Author and Founder of FiveThirtyEight \u2013 Joins ESPN in Multi-Faceted Role\", [http://frontrow.espn.go.com/2013/07/nate-silver-renowned-statistician-author-and-founder-of-fivethirtyeight-joins-espn-in-multi-faceted-role/ ESPN Front Row, July 22, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725173226/http://frontrow.espn.go.com/2013/07/nate-silver-renowned-statistician-author-and-founder-of-fivethirtyeight-joins-espn-in-multi-faceted-role/ |date=July 25, 2013 }}.</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' public editor [[Margaret Sullivan (journalist)|Margaret Sullivan]] wrote upon Silver's decision to leave for ESPN:\n\n<blockquote>I don't think Nate Silver ever really fit into the Times culture and I think he was aware of that. He was, in a word, disruptive. Much like the [[Brad Pitt]] character in the movie \"[[Moneyball (film)|Moneyball]]\" disrupted the old model of how to scout baseball players, Nate disrupted the traditional model of how to cover politics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sullivan|first=Margaret|title=Nate Silver Went Against the Grain for Some at The Times|url=http://publiceditor.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/07/22/nate-silver-went-against-the-grain-for-some-at-the-times/?smid=tw-share|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=23 July 2013|date=July 22, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018064539/http://publiceditor.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/07/22/nate-silver-went-against-the-grain-for-some-at-the-times/?smid=tw-share|archive-date=October 18, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nShe added, \"A number of traditional and well-respected Times journalists disliked his work.\"<ref>On the culture clash within ''The Times,'' also see John Sides, \"One Irony of Nate Silver's Leaving the New York Times\", ''[[Washington Monthly]]'', [http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/ten-miles-square/2013/07/one_irony_of_nate_silvers_leav045992.php# July 24, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105025859/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/ten-miles-square/2013/07/one_irony_of_nate_silvers_leav045992.php |date=November 5, 2013 }}; and Jim Naureckas, \"Nate Silver Didn't Fit In at the New York Times Because He Believed in the Real World\", [[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting|FAIR]], [http://www.fair.org/blog/2013/07/24/nate-silver-didnt-fit-in-at-the-new-york-times-because-he-believed-in-the-real-world/ July 24, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728114443/http://www.fair.org/blog/2013/07/24/nate-silver-didnt-fit-in-at-the-new-york-times-because-he-believed-in-the-real-world/ |date=July 28, 2013 }}.</ref> Later, Sullivan wrote in ''The Times'' that \"I don't feel so good about not being able to investigate every complaint from every individual reader fully, or about making some misjudgments in individual posts \u2014 my Nate Silver commentary, among others, has probably been off-base...\".<ref>Although she linked to her \"Nate Silver Went Against the Grain\" article, Sullivan did not specify in what ways she had been off-base. See Margaret Sullivan, \"A Year in the Life of a Watchdog\", ''The New York Times'', September 1, 2013.</ref>\n\n[[New York (magazine)|''New York'']] magazine reported that executive editor Jill Abramson \"put on a full-court press\" to keep Silver at ''The Times'' and that \"for Abramson, Silver was a tentpole attraction for her favorite subject, national politics, and brought the kind of buzz she thought valuable\", but the company's CEO and President [[Mark Thompson (television executive)|Mark Thompson]] \"confirmed that keeping Silver was not at the top of his agenda\". The article stated that \"the major reason Silver left was because he felt it was Thompson who had not committed to building his franchise. The mixed signals from Thompson and Abramson\u2014his lack of enthusiasm for committing resources to Silver, her desire to keep a major star\u2014frustrated Silver and his lawyer\".<ref>Joe Hagan, \"The Suit in the Newsroom: An unusual Times executive\u2014for unusual times\", [[New York (magazine)|''New York'']], [http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/new-york-times-mark-thompson-2013-9/ August 23, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823205937/http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/new-york-times-mark-thompson-2013-9/ |date=August 23, 2013 }}.</ref>\n\n====''FiveThirtyEight'' under ESPN ownership====\nWhen ''FiveThirtyEight'' was relaunched under ESPN's ownership on March 17, 2014, Silver outlined the scope of topics that would be covered under the rubric of \"data journalism\":<ref name=\"March 17, 2014\"/>\n\n{{quote|We've expanded our staff from two full-time journalists to 20 and counting. Few of them will focus on politics exclusively; instead, our coverage will span five major subject areas \u2014 politics, economics, science, life and sports.\n\nOur team also has a broad set of skills and experience in methods that fall under the rubric of data journalism. These include statistical analysis, but also data visualization, computer programming and data-literate reporting. So in addition to written stories, we'll have interactive graphics and features. Within a couple of months we'll launch a podcast, and we'll be collaborating with [[ESPN Films]] and [[Grantland]] to produce original documentary films.}}\n\n===''FiveThirtyEight's'' election forecasts===\n\n====2008 U.S. elections====\n{{Main|FiveThirtyEight}}\nIn March 2008, Silver established his blog ''FiveThirtyEight.com,'' in which he developed a system for tracking polls and forecasting the outcome of the 2008 [[general election]]. At the same time, he continued making forecasts of the [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2008|2008 Democratic primary elections]]. That several of his forecasts based on [[demographic analysis]] proved to be substantially more accurate than those of the professional [[pollsters]] gained visibility and professional credibility for \"Poblano\", the pseudonym that Silver was then using.<ref>See, most notably, Mark Blumenthal, \"The Poblano Model\", [http://www.nationaljournal.com/njonline/mp_20080507_8254.php ''[[National Journal]],'' May 8, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414152429/http://www.nationaljournal.com/njonline/mp_20080507_8254.php |date=April 14, 2009 }}.</ref>\n\nAfter the North Carolina and Indiana primaries on May 6, the popularity of ''FiveThirtyEight.com'' surged. Silver recalls the scenario: 'I know the polls show it's really tight in NC, but we think Obama is going to win by thirteen, fourteen points, and he did. ... Any time you make a prediction like that people give you probably too much credit for it.... But after that [Silver's and the website's popularity] started to really take off. It's pretty nonlinear, once you get one mention in the mainstream media, other people [quickly follow suit]'\".<ref>Sean Redmond, \"Numerical Order: Famed Statistician Nate Silver Discusses the Future of His Near-Flawless Forecasts\", [http://chicagoweekly.net/2009/01/09/numerical-order-famed-statistician-nate-silver-discusses-the-future-of-his-near-flawless-forecasting/ ''[[Chicago Weekly]]'', January 9, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927024826/http://chicagoweekly.net/2009/01/09/numerical-order-famed-statistician-nate-silver-discusses-the-future-of-his-near-flawless-forecasting/ |date=September 27, 2010 }} . On this point see also Silver's discussion in Megan Garber, \"Talking Shop: Nate Silver\", [http://www.cjr.org/campaign_desk/talking_shop_nate_silver.php ''Columbia Journalism Review'', November 11, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081116055812/http://www.cjr.org/campaign_desk/talking_shop_nate_silver.php |date=November 16, 2008 }}.</ref>\n\nAs a [[CNET]] reporter wrote on election eve, \"Even though Silver launched the site as recently as March, its straightforward approach, daring predictions, and short but impressive track record has put it on the map of political sites to follow. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' featured Silver in its 14th annual election prediction contest this year, and he'll be reporting on Tuesday night's results with [[Dan Rather]] on [[HDNet]]\".<ref>Stephanie Condon, \"Q & A: The Formula Behind FiveThirtyEight\", [http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-10080885-38.html?part=rsssubj=newstag=2547-1_3-0-20 ''CNET News'', November 3, 2008].</ref>\n\nSilver's final 2008 presidential election forecast accurately predicted the winner of 49 of the 50 states as well as the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] (missing only the prediction for Indiana). As his model predicted, the races in [[Missouri]] and [[North Carolina]] were particularly close. He also correctly predicted the winners of every [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] race.  The accuracy of his predictions won him further acclaim, including abroad,<ref>Editorial, \"In Praise of ... Nate Silver\", [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/06/us-elections-nate-silver-predictions ''The Guardian'', November 6, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121173722/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/06/us-elections-nate-silver-predictions |date=November 21, 2016 }}.</ref> and added to his reputation as a leading political prognosticator.<ref>Stephanie Clifford, \"Finding Fame With a Prescient Call for Obama\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/10/business/media/10silver.html?scp=5&sq=Stephanie%20Clifford&st=cse ''The New York Times'', November 10, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821125255/https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/10/business/media/10silver.html?scp=5&sq=Stephanie%20Clifford&st=cse |date=August 21, 2018 }}.</ref>\n\n[[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign]] signed off on a proposal to share all of its private polling with Silver. After signing a confidentiality agreement, Silver was granted access to hundreds of polls the campaign had conducted.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Victory Lab|last=  Issenberg|first=Sasha |authorlink= |publisher= [[Crown Publishing Group]] |location= |isbn=030795479X |page= 290 |pages= |url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=BuzzFeed Politics |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/buzzfeedpolitics/obama-campaign-shared-08-polling-with-silver |title=\"Obama Campaign Shared '08 Polling With Silver\" '&#39;BuzzFeed,'&#39; September 5, 2012 |publisher=Buzzfeed.com |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026135718/http://www.buzzfeed.com/buzzfeedpolitics/obama-campaign-shared-08-polling-with-silver |archive-date=October 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====2010 U.S. elections====\n{{Main|FiveThirtyEight#2010 U.S. mid-term elections}}\nShortly after ''FiveThirtyEight'' relocated to ''The New York Times'', Silver introduced his prediction models for the 2010 elections to the U.S. Senate, the U.S. House of Representatives, and state governorships. Each of these models relied initially on a combination of electoral history, demographics, and polling. Silver eventually published detailed forecasts and analyses of the results for all three sets of elections. He correctly predicted the winner in 34 of the 37 contested Senate races.  His 2010 congressional mid-term predictions were not as accurate as those made in 2008, but were still within the reported [[confidence interval]]. Silver predicted a Republican pickup of 54 seats in the House of Representatives; the GOP won 63 seats. Of the 37 gubernatorial races, ''FiveThirtyEight'' correctly predicted the winner of 36.<ref>Micah Cohen, \"38 Days Later\", ''The New York Times'', [http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/10/38-days-later/ December 10, 2010] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011154100/http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/10/38-days-later/ |date=October 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====2012 U.S. elections====\n{{Main|FiveThirtyEight#2012_U.S._elections|l1=FiveThirtyEight: 2012 U.S. elections}}\nAlthough throughout 2011 Silver devoted a lot of attention on his blog to the 2012 Republican party primaries, his first effort to handicap the 2012 Presidential general election appeared as the cover story in ''The New York Times Magazine'' a year prior to the election: \"Is Obama Toast? Handicapping the 2012 Election\".<ref>Nate Silver, \"Is Obama Toast? Handicapping the 2012 Election\", [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/06/magazine/nate-silver-handicaps-2012-election.html ''The New York Times Magazine'', November 6, 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227224935/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/06/magazine/nate-silver-handicaps-2012-election.html |date=February 27, 2017 }}.</ref> Accompanying the online release of this article, Silver also published \"Choose Obama's Re-Election Adventure\", an interactive toy that allowed readers to predict the outcome of the election based on their assumptions about three variables: President Obama's favorability ratings, the rate of GDP growth, and how conservative the Republican opponent would be.<ref>Nate Silver, \"Choose Obama's Re-Election Adventure\", [http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/03/choose-obamas-re-election-adventure/ ''The New York Times'', November 3, 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910081523/http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/03/choose-obamas-re-election-adventure/ |date=September 10, 2015 }}</ref> This analysis stimulated a lot of critical discussion.<ref>For a partial bibliography, see Micah Cohen, \"Reads and Reactions\", [http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/19/reads-reactions-14/ ''The New York Times'', November 19, 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009150020/http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/19/reads-reactions-14/ |date=October 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nWhile publishing numerous stories on the Republican primary elections, in mid-February 2012 Silver reprised and updated his previous ''Magazine'' story with another one, \"What Obama Should Do Next\".<ref>Nate Silver, \"Why Obama Will Embrace the 99 Percent\", [http://www.vanityfair.com/business/features/2011/09/europe-201109 ''The New York Times Magazine'', February 15, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207210341/http://www.vanityfair.com/business/features/2011/09/europe-201109 |date=February 7, 2012 }}.</ref> This story painted a more optimistic picture of President Obama's re-election chances. A companion article on his ''FiveThirtyEight'' blog, \"The Fundamentals Now Favor Obama\", explained how the model and the facts on the ground had changed between November and February.<ref>Nate Silver, \"The Fundamentals Now Favor Obama\", [http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/15/the-fundamentals-now-favor-obama/ ''The New York Times'', February 15, 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906152909/http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/15/the-fundamentals-now-favor-obama/ |date=September 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nSilver published the first iteration of his 2012 general election forecasts on June 7, 2012. According to the model, at that time Barack Obama was projected to win 291 electoral votes\u201421 more than the 270 required for a majority. Obama then had an estimated 61.8% chance of winning a majority.<ref>Nate Silver, \"Election Forecast: Obama Begins With Tenuous Advantage\", [http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/07/election-forecast-obama-begins-with-tenuous-advantage/#more-31097 ''The New York Times'', June 7, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911020537/http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/07/election-forecast-obama-begins-with-tenuous-advantage/#more-31097 |date=September 11, 2015 }}.</ref>\n\nOn the morning of the November 6, 2012, presidential election, the final update of Silver's model at 10:10 A.M. gave President Barack Obama a 90.9% chance of winning a majority of the 538 electoral votes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Silver|first=Nate|url=http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/|title=FiveThirtyEight/NYT blog|publisher=Fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com|accessdate=December 5, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425170119/http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/|archive-date=April 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Both in summary tables and in an electoral map, Silver forecast the winner of each state. At the conclusion of that day, when Mitt Romney had conceded to Barack Obama, Silver's model had correctly predicted the winner of every one of the 50 states and the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]].<ref>Daniel Terdiman, \"[http://news.cnet.com/8301-13510_3-57546161-21/obamas-win-a-big-vindication-for-nate-silver-king-of-the-quants/ Obama's win a big vindication for Nate Silver, king of the quants] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107201118/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13510_3-57546161-21/obamas-win-a-big-vindication-for-nate-silver-king-of-the-quants/ |date=November 7, 2012 }}\", [[CNET]], November 6, 2012.</ref><ref>Although Silver put a \"toss-up\" tag on the presidential election in Florida, his interactive electoral map on the website painted the state light blue and stated that there was a 50.3% probability that Obama would win a plurality of the state's votes.</ref> Silver, along with at least three<ref>A fourth analyst, [[Sam Wang (neuroscientist)|Sam Wang]], missed only the State of Florida in his final presidential election forecast. See Sam Wang, \"Presidential prediction 2012 \u2013 final\", ''Princeton Election Connection,'' [http://election.princeton.edu/2012/11/06/presidential-prediction-2012-final/ November 6, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116022709/https://election.princeton.edu/2012/11/06/presidential-prediction-2012-final/ |date=November 16, 2012 }}.</ref> academic-based analysts\u2014[[Drew Linzer]],<ref>\"Emory professor called Electoral landslide in June\", [http://www.ajc.com/news/news/emory-professor-called-electoral-landslide-in-june/nS2Wj/ ''[[Atlanta Journal and Constitution]]'', November 8, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114023732/http://www.ajc.com/news/news/emory-professor-called-electoral-landslide-in-june/nS2Wj/ |date=November 14, 2012 }}.</ref> Simon Jackman,<ref>Simon Jackman, \"Pollster Predictive Performance, 51 out of 51\", [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/simon-jackman/pollster-predictive-perfo_b_2087862.html ''[[Huffington Post]]'', November 7, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309231920/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/simon-jackman/pollster-predictive-perfo_b_2087862.html |date=March 9, 2013 }}</ref> and Josh Putnam<ref>Josh Putnam, \"The Electoral College Map (11/6/12): Election Day\", [http://frontloading.blogspot.com/2012/11/the-electoral-college-map-11612.html FHQ (FrontloadingHQ), November 6, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110072133/http://frontloading.blogspot.com/2012/11/the-electoral-college-map-11612.html |date=November 10, 2012 }}.</ref>\u2014who also [[Poll aggregator|aggregated polls]] from multiple pollsters\u2014thus was not only broadly correct about the election outcome, but also specifically predicted the outcomes for the nine ''[[swing state]]s''.<ref>Swing states in the 2012 election were Colorado, Florida, Iowa, Nevada, New Hampshire, North Carolina, Ohio, Virginia, and Wisconsin</ref> In contrast, individual pollsters were less successful. For example, Rasmussen Reports \"missed on six of its nine swing-state polls\".<ref>Jonathan D. Salant and Laura Curtis, \"Nate Silver-led Statistics Men Crush Pundits in Election\", ''[http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-11-07/nate-silver-led-statistics-men-crush-pundits-in-election Bloomberg Business Week] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108063430/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-11-07/nate-silver-led-statistics-men-crush-pundits-in-election |date=November 8, 2012 }}'', November 7, 2012.</ref><ref>The reason for these misses might be found here: John Sides, \"A Second Look at National Pollster Accuracy\", ''The Monkey Cage'', November 7, 2012. [retrieved Nov 8, 2012]. However, notably [[Public Policy Polling]] by itself correctly predicted the [http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/final_2012_polls/#top winner of every state] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109114035/http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/final_2012_polls/#top |date=November 9, 2012 }}.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Slate's Pundit Scorecard: Pundits live to make predictions. Who nailed it? Who missed big?|date=November 7, 2012|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2012/11/pundit_scorecard_checking_pundits_predictions_against_the_actual_results.html|last=Stern|first=Mark Joseph|last2=Kirk|first2=Chris|last3=Morgan|first3=Andrew|accessdate=September 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060321/http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2012/11/pundit_scorecard_checking_pundits_predictions_against_the_actual_results.html|archive-date=September 21, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== 2016 U.S. elections ====\n{{Main|FiveThirtyEight#2016 U.S. elections|l1=FiveThirtyEight: 2016 U.S. elections}}\nIn the week leading up to the [[2016 U.S. presidential election]], the ''FiveThirtyEight'' team predicted that [[Hillary Clinton]] had a 64.5% chance of winning the election. Their final prediction on November 8, 2016, gave Clinton a 71% chance to win the [[2016 United States presidential election]],<ref>{{cite web|title = Final Election Update: There's A Wide Range Of Outcomes, And Most Of Them Come Up Clinton|url = http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/final-election-update-theres-a-wide-range-of-outcomes-and-most-of-them-come-up-clinton/|website = FiveThirtyEight|access-date = November 9, 2016|language = en-US|first = Nate|last = Silver|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161109044042/http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/final-election-update-theres-a-wide-range-of-outcomes-and-most-of-them-come-up-clinton/|archive-date = November 9, 2016|url-status = live}}</ref> while other major forecasters had predicted Clinton to win with at least an 85% to 99% probability.<ref name=\"Silver5\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/uselection/2016/11/09/nate-silvers-fivethirtyeight-proves-its-worth-with-another-close-election-prediction.html|title=Nate Silver's FiveThirtyEight proves its worth with another close election prediction|last=Allen|first=Kate|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=November 9, 2016|accessdate=November 10, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109095542/https://www.thestar.com/news/world/uselection/2016/11/09/nate-silvers-fivethirtyeight-proves-its-worth-with-another-close-election-prediction.html|archive-date=November 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Donald Trump]] won the election.  ''FiveThirtyEight'' argued it projected a much higher chance (29%) of Donald Trump winning the presidency than other pollsters,<ref name=\"Silver5\">[http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-fivethirtyeight-gave-trump-a-better-chance-than-almost-anyone-else/ Why FiveThirtyEight Gave Trump A Better Chance Than Almost Anyone Else] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114003644/http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-fivethirtyeight-gave-trump-a-better-chance-than-almost-anyone-else/ |date=November 14, 2016 }}; ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]''; Nate Silver; November 11, 2016</ref> a projection which was criticized days before the election by [[Ryan Grim]] of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' as \"unskewing\" too much in favor of Trump.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/nate-silver-election-forecast_us_581e1c33e4b0d9ce6fbc6f7f? Nate Silver Is Unskewing Polls \u2014 All Of Them \u2014 In Trump's Direction] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114004104/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/nate-silver-election-forecast_us_581e1c33e4b0d9ce6fbc6f7f |date=November 14, 2016 }}; ''[[Huffington Post]]''; Ryan Grim; November 5, 2016</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nSilver has been criticized for inaccurate predictions. In January 2010, journalist and blogger [[Colby Cosh]] criticized Silver's performance during the [[United States Senate special election in Massachusetts, 2010|Massachusetts special Senate election]], saying he was \"still arguing as late as Thursday afternoon that [[Martha Coakley|[Martha] Coakley]] was the clear favourite; he changed his mind at midnight that evening and acknowledged that [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]] had a puncher's chance.\" (Brown won the election.)<ref>{{cite news|last=Cosh|first=Colby|title=Mr. Overrated|url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2010/01/19/mr-overrated/|accessdate=November 6, 2012|newspaper=Macleans|date=January 19, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106015912/http://www2.macleans.ca/2010/01/19/mr-overrated/|archive-date=November 6, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSilver's quantitative focus on polling data, without insight from experience in political organizing or journalism, has been a recurring critique from experienced commentators. ''Huffington Post'' columnist Geoffrey Dunn described Silver as someone who \"has never organized a precinct in his life, much less walked one, pontificating about the dynamics in the electoral processes as if he actually understood them.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Dunn|first=Geoffrey|title=FiveThirtyHate?: Nate Silver Gets His Numbers Crossed in Charlotte|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/geoffrey-dunn/fivethirtyhate-nate-silve_b_1863634.html|accessdate=November 3, 2012|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=September 7, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012094933/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/geoffrey-dunn/fivethirtyhate-nate-silve_b_1863634.html|archive-date=October 12, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nConsiderable criticism during the 2012 elections came from political conservatives, who argued that Silver's election projections were politically biased against [[Mitt Romney]], the Republican candidate for President.<ref>Gregory Ferenstein, \"[https://techcrunch.com/2012/10/30/why-pundits-and-politicians-hate-nyt-election-forecaster-nate-silver/ Why Pundits and Politicians Hate NYT Election Forecaster Nate Silver] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117080632/https://techcrunch.com/2012/10/30/why-pundits-and-politicians-hate-nyt-election-forecaster-nate-silver/ |date=November 17, 2017 }}\", [[TechCrunch]], October 30, 2012.</ref> For example, Silver was accused of applying a double standard to his treatment of [[Rasmussen Reports]] polls, such as a 2010 analysis asserting a statistical bias in its methodology.<ref>Nate Silver, \"Rasmussen Polls Were Biased and Inaccurate; Quinnipiac, SurveyUSA Performed Strongly\", [http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/04/rasmussen-polls-were-biased-and-inaccurate-quinnipiac-surveyusa-performed-strongly/ ''FiveThirtyEight'', November 4, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108143725/http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/04/rasmussen-polls-were-biased-and-inaccurate-quinnipiac-surveyusa-performed-strongly/ |date=November 8, 2012 }}.</ref> Josh Jordan wrote in ''[[National Review]]'' that Silver clearly favored Obama and adjusted the weight he gave polls \"based on what [he] think[s] of the pollster and the results and not based on what is actually inside the poll\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Jordan|first=Josh|title=Nate Silver's Flawed Model|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/331192/nate-silver-s-flawed-model-josh-jordan|accessdate=November 3, 2012|newspaper=National Review|date=October 22, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102181845/http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/331192/nate-silver-s-flawed-model-josh-jordan|archive-date=November 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[Morning Joe]]'', host [[Joe Scarborough]] stated that Silver's prediction that day of a 73.6% chance of a win for Obama greatly exceeded the confidence of the Obama campaign itself, which Scarborough equated to that of the Romney campaign, both believing \"they have a 50.1 percent chance of winning\", and calling Silver an \"ideologue\" and a \"joke\". Silver responded with the offer of a $1,000 wager (for charity) over the outcome of the election. ''The New York Times'' public editor Margaret Sullivan, while defending Silver's analysis, characterized the wager as \"a bad idea\" as it gave the appearance of a partisan motive for Silver, and \"inappropriate\" for someone perceived as a ''Times'' journalist (although Silver was not a member of the newspaper's staff).<ref>{{cite news|last=Sullivan|first=Margaret|title=Under Attack, Nate Silver Picks the Wrong Defense|url=http://publiceditor.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/01/under-attack-nate-silver-picks-the-wrong-defense/|accessdate=November 3, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102233053/http://publiceditor.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/01/under-attack-nate-silver-picks-the-wrong-defense/|archive-date=November 2, 2012|url-status=live}}. For a critical comment see Andrew Beaujon, \"[http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/194020/new-york-times-wants-to-hold-nate-silver-to-newsroom-standards/ New York Times wants to hold Nate Silver to newsroom standards]\", [[Poynter Institute|Poynter]], November 2, 2012 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115005935/http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/194020/new-york-times-wants-to-hold-nate-silver-to-newsroom-standards/ |date=November 15, 2012 }}</ref><ref>For discussion of another \"pundits vs. Nate Silver\" case, see John Cassidy, \"[http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2012/10/david-brooks-v-nate-silver-prediction-polls.html Brooks vs. Silver: The Limits of Forecasting Elections] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114101729/http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2012/10/david-brooks-v-nate-silver-prediction-polls.html |date=November 14, 2012 }}\", ''[[The New Yorker]]'', October 24, 2012.</ref>\n\nAfter a post-election appearance by Silver on Joe Scarborough's ''Morning Joe'', Scarborough published what he called a \"(semi) apology\", in which he concluded:\n\n{{Quote|I won't apologize to Mr. Silver for predicting an outcome that I had also been predicting for a year. But I do need to tell Nate I'm sorry for leaning in too hard and lumping him with pollsters whose methodology is as rigorous as [[the Simpsons]]' strip mall physician, [[Dr. Nick]]. For those sins (and a multitude of others that I'm sure I don't even know about), I am sorry.\n\nPolitics is a messy sport. And just as ball players who drink beer and eat fried chicken in dugouts across America can screw up the smartest sabermetrician's forecast, Nate Silver's formula is sure to let his fervent admirers down from time to time. But judging from what I saw of him this morning, Nate is a grounded guy who admits as much in his book. I was too tough on him and there's a 84.398264% chance I will be less dismissive of his good work in the future\".<ref>Joe Scarborough, \"My (Semi) Apology to Nate Silver\", ''Politico,'' [http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1112/84115.html November 21, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121123191838/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1112/84115.html |date=November 23, 2012 }}.</ref>}}\n\nSilver's nondisclosure of the details of his analytical model has resulted in some skepticism. [[The Washington Post|''Washington Post'']] journalist [[Ezra Klein]] wrote: \"There are good criticisms to make of Silver's model, not the least of which is that, while Silver is almost tediously detailed about what's going on in the model, he won't give out the code, and without the code, we can't say with certainty how the model works.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Klein|first=Ezra|title=The Nate Silver backlash|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2012/10/30/the-nate-silver-backlash/|accessdate=November 3, 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=October 30, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130035831/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2012/10/30/the-nate-silver-backlash/|archive-date=November 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Colby Cosh wrote that the model \"is proprietary and irreproducible. That last feature makes it unwise to use Silver's model as a straw stand-in for \"science\", as if the model had been fully specified in a peer-reviewed journal\".<ref>\"Nate Silver and the Trials of a Forecaster\", [http://www.threehundredeight.com/2012/11/nate-silver-and-trials-of-forecaster.html ThreeHundredEight.com, November 6, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109045008/http://www.threehundredeight.com/2012/11/nate-silver-and-trials-of-forecaster.html |date=November 9, 2012 }}.</ref>\n\n==The Signal and the Noise==\n{{main|The Signal and the Noise}}\n[[File:Nate Silver at SXSW 2013.jpg|thumb|right|Silver signing a copy of ''The Signal and the Noise'' at [[South by Southwest|SXSW]] 2013]]\n\n''The Signal and The Noise'' was published in the United States on September 27, 2012. It reached the [[New York Times Best Sellers List]] as #12 for non-fiction hardback books after its first week in print. It dropped to #20 in the second week, before rising to #13 in the third, and remaining on the non-fiction hardback top 15 list for the following 13 weeks, with a highest weekly ranking of #4.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cowles |first=Gregory |url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html |title=New York Times Best Sellers List |publisher=Nytimes.com |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205214736/http://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html |archive-date=December 5, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sales increased after the election on November 6, jumping 800% and becoming the second best seller on [[Amazon.com]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Notte |title=Nate Silver sees soaring Amazon book sales: The FiveThirtyEight blogger's confident and steadfast Obama forecast gets readers curious and critics furious |url=http://money.msn.com/top-stocks/post.aspx?post=3d424e42-2010-4c0d-abed-340c55f00240&ocid=ansmony11 |publisher=[[MSN Money]] |date=November 8, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115174458/http://money.msn.com/top-stocks/post.aspx?post=3d424e42-2010-4c0d-abed-340c55f00240&ocid=ansmony11 |archivedate=January 15, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nThe book describes methods of mathematical model-building using [[probability]] and statistics. Silver takes a big-picture approach to using statistical tools, combining sources of unique data (e.g., timing a minor league ball player's fastball using a radar gun), with historical data and principles of sound statistical analysis; Silver argues that many of these are violated by many pollsters and pundits who nonetheless have important media roles. Case studies in the book include baseball, elections, [[climate change]], the financial crash, poker, and weather forecasting. These different topics illustrate different statistical principles. As a reviewer in ''The New York Times'' notes: \"It's largely about evaluating predictions in a variety of fields, from finance to weather to epidemiology. We learn about a handful of successes: when, for instance, meteorologists predict a hurricane's landfall 72 hours in advance.... But mostly we learn about failures. It turns out we're not even close to predicting the next catastrophic earthquake or the spread of the next killer bird flu, despite the enormous amounts of brainpower trained on these questions in the past few decades\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Noam |last=Scheiber |title=Known Unknowns: ''The Signal and the Noise,'' by Nate Silver |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/04/books/review/the-signal-and-the-noise-by-nate-silver.html |date=November 2, 2012 |accessdate=October 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006220101/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/04/books/review/the-signal-and-the-noise-by-nate-silver.html |archive-date=October 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Blogs and other publications==\n;Blogs\n* [http://fivethirtyeight.com ''FiveThirtyEight'' blog, now owned by ABC]\n* [https://www.baseballprospectus.com/author/nate_silver/ Nate Silver's ''Baseball Prospectus'' article archive] (2003\u20132009)\n* [http://burritobracket.blogspot.com/ Nate Silver's ''The Burrito Bracket''] (2007)\n\n;Other publications\n* Nate Silver, \"The Most Livable Neighborhoods in New York: A Quantitative Index of the 50 Most Satisfying Places to Live\", ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]],'' [http://nymag.com/realestate/neighborhoods/2010/65374/ April 11, 2010].\n* Nate Silver, \"The Influence Index\", ''Time,'' [http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1984685_1984713_1984669,00.html April 29, 2010].\n* Nate Silver and Walter Hickey, \"Best Picture Math\", ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]],'' [http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/03/oscar-winner-predictions-nate-silver March 2014].\n* [[Gareth Cook]] (Editor), Nate Silver (Introduction). ''The Best American Infographics 2014'', Houghton Mifflin Harcourt. {{isbn|978-0547974514}}.\n* Review of two children's books, with an autobiographical comment: \"Beautiful Minds: ''The Boy Who Loved Math'' and ''On a Beam of Light''\", ''The New York Times'', [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/14/books/review/the-boy-who-loved-math-and-on-a-beam-of-light.html July 12, 2013].\n* [[Andrew Gelman]], Nate Silver, Aaron S. Edlin, \"What Is the Probability Your Vote Will Make a Difference\", ''[[Economic Inquiry]]'', 2012, 50(2): 321\u201326.\n*In addition to chapters in several issues of the ''Baseball Prospectus'' annual, Silver contributed chapters to one-off monographs edited by [[Baseball Prospectus]], including:\n**''Mind Game: How the Boston Red Sox Got Smart, Won a World Series, and Created a New Blueprint for Winning''. Steven Goldman, Ed. New York: Workman Publishing Co., 2005. {{isbn|0-7611-4018-2}}.\n**''Baseball Between the Numbers: Why Everything You Know about the Game Is Wrong''. Jonah Keri, Ed. New York: Basic Books, 2006. {{isbn|0-465-00596-9}} (hardback) and {{isbn|0-465-00547-0}} (paperback).\n**''It Ain't over 'til It's over: The Baseball Prospectus Pennant Race Book''. Steven Goldman, Ed. New York: Basic Books. Hardback 2007. {{isbn|0-465-00284-6}}; paperback 2008. {{isbn|0-465-00285-4}}.\n\n==Media==\nSilver's self-unmasking at the end of May 2008 brought him a lot of publicity focused on his combined skill as both baseball statistician-forecaster and political statistician-forecaster, including articles about him in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>[[Carl Bialik]], \"Baseball Analyst Draws Fans by Crunching Election Numbers\", [https://blogs.wsj.com/numbersguy/baseball-analyst-draws-fans-by-crunching-election-numbers-347/ ''The Wall Street Journal'', June 2, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606201959/https://blogs.wsj.com/numbersguy/baseball-analyst-draws-fans-by-crunching-election-numbers-347/ |date=June 6, 2008 }}.</ref> ''[[Newsweek]]'',<ref>Andrew Romano, \"Making His Pitches: Nate Silver, an all-star in the world of baseball stats, may be the political arena's next big draw\", [http://www.newsweek.com/id/140469 ''[[Newsweek]]'', June 16, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080619111251/http://www.newsweek.com/id/140469 |date=June 19, 2008 }},</ref> ''[[Science News]]'',<ref>Julie Rehmeyer, \"Scooping the Political Pollsters\", [http://www.sciencenews.org/view/generic/id/34036/title/Math_Trek__Scooping_the_political_pollsters ''[[Science News]]'', July 11, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080716002337/http://www.sciencenews.org/view/generic/id/34036/title/Math_Trek__Scooping_the_political_pollsters |date=July 16, 2008 }}.</ref><ref>Adam Sternbergh, \"The Spreadsheet Psychic\", [http://nymag.com/news/features/51170/ ''[[New York Magazine]]'', October 12, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081017181340/http://nymag.com/news/features/51170/ |date=October 17, 2008 }}.</ref> and his hometown ''[[Lansing State Journal]]''.<ref>Derek Wallbank, \"E. L. native's predictions pitch politics a curveball: Applying baseball stats analysis creates buzz around 30-year-old\", ''[[Lansing State Journal]]'', July 5, 2008. Also highlighting Silver's dual skills at baseball and political analysis were Alex Altman, \"Q & A: Political Pollster Nate Silver\", [http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1847387,00.html ''[[Time (Magazine)|Time]]'', October 6, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009042651/http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1847387,00.html |date=October 9, 2008 }}, Joe Lemire, \"The Sports-Politics Connection: FiveThirtyEight\", [http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1146193/index.htm ''Sports Illustrated'', October 13, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012092545/http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1146193/index.htm |date=October 12, 2008 }}, James Janega, \"Odds are, he knows the score&nbsp;\u2013 Chicago statistician Nate Silver has turned from sports to politics, with striking results\", [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-stats-guru-27-oct27,0,6651423.story ''Chicago Tribune'', October 27, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028164502/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-stats-guru-27-oct27,0,6651423.story |date=October 28, 2008 }}, Ben Heller, \"[http://www.sportsline.com/print/spin/story/11090208 The 2008 Sports Nerd of the Year: Nate Silver]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\", [[CBSSports.com]], November 7, 2008. and Childs Walker, \"[http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/sports/thetoydepartment/2009/04/projecting_politics_baseball_w_1.html Projecting politics & baseball with Nate Silver] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411112140/http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/sports/thetoydepartment/2009/04/projecting_politics_baseball_w_1.html |date=April 11, 2009 }}\", ''[[Baltimore Sun]]'', April 8, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn early June he began to cross-post his daily \"Today's Polls\" updates on \"The Plank\" in ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref>The first such posting was Nate Silver, \"Today's Polls: The Bounce Hits the Badger State\", ''The New Republic'', [http://blogs.tnr.com/tnr/blogs/the_plank/archive/2008/06/12/today-s-polls-the-bounce-hits-the-badger-state.aspx June 12, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614232907/http://blogs.tnr.com/tnr/blogs/the_plank/archive/2008/06/12/today-s-polls-the-bounce-hits-the-badger-state.aspx |date=June 14, 2008 }}</ref> Also, ''[[Rasmussen Reports]]'' began to use the ''FiveThirtyEight.com'' poll averages for its own tracking of the 2008 state-by-state races.<ref>\"Rasmussen Reports to Partner with FiveThirtyEight.com\", ''[[Democratic Underground]],'' [http://www.democraticunderground.com/discuss/duboard.php?az=view_all&address=132x6361757 June 14, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116024716/http://www.democraticunderground.com/discuss/duboard.php?az=view_all&address=132x6361757 |date=January 16, 2013 }}. [retrieved November 27, 2012]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 through 2012, Silver appeared as a political analyst on MSNBC,<ref>\nFor example,[https://archive.today/20120721171031/http://www.bing.com/videos/watch/video/poll-watchers-waiting-for-iowans-to-settle/61r3p7d?cpkey=74c63c86-8176-4fd2-a1a1-95f020b6cc85 the Rachel Maddow show] on December 28, 2011, as well as [https://web.archive.org/web/20120419085031/http://video.msnbc.msn.com/the-rachel-maddow-show/45851722#45851722a January 2, 2012]  \n</ref> CNN<ref>For example, an interview by [[Howard Kurtz]] on ''[[Reliable Sources]]'' on September 25, 2011: {{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/politics/2011/09/25/rs-nate-silver-part-1.cnn |title=Interview Part 1 |work=[[Reliable Sources]] |author= |date=September 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204210432/http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/politics/2011/09/25/rs-nate-silver-part-1.cnn |archivedate=2009-02-04 |url-status=dead}} ; {{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/politics/2011/09/25/rs-nate-silver-part-2.cnn |title=Interview Part 2 |work=[[Reliable Sources]] |author= |date=September 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204210432/http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/politics/2011/09/25/rs-nate-silver-part-2.cnn |archivedate=2009-02-04 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Bloomberg Television]],<ref>{{cite web|author=bizbuzz3|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cfPCNI3ifDg|title=Video of Nate Silver on Bloomberg, March 8, 2010|publisher=Youtube.com|date=November 3, 2008|accessdate=August 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218023905/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cfPCNI3ifDg|archive-date=February 18, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\"Nate Silver: Why Gun Rights Rhetoric Is Winning\", [https://www.bloomberg.com/video/nate-silver-why-guns-rights-rhetoric-is-winning-cm3jd2o9RjaIAvS_B4qEyw.html December 17, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105023204/http://www.bloomberg.com/video/nate-silver-why-guns-rights-rhetoric-is-winning-cm3jd2o9RjaIAvS_B4qEyw.html |date=November 5, 2013 }}.</ref> [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/need-to-know/video/nate-silver-on-why-the-polls-dont-always-add-up/4289/|title=Need to Know: Nate Silver on Why Polls Don't Always Add Up|publisher=Pbs.org|date=October 15, 2010|accessdate=August 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308014556/http://www.pbs.org/wnet/need-to-know/video/nate-silver-on-why-the-polls-dont-always-add-up/4289/|archive-date=March 8, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> NPR,<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2011/08/02/138935743/whats-the-electoral-impact-of-the-debt-ceiling-debate What's the Impact of the Debt Debate, August 2, 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827115527/https://www.npr.org/2011/08/02/138935743/whats-the-electoral-impact-of-the-debt-ceiling-debate |date=August 27, 2018 }}.</ref> ''[[Democracy Now!]]'',<ref>[http://www.democracynow.org/2010/5/18/on_mini_super_tuesday_3_senate Democracy Now 5-18-2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100521173034/http://www.democracynow.org/2010/5/18/on_mini_super_tuesday_3_senate |date=May 21, 2010 }}.</ref> ''The Charlie Rose Show'',<ref>\ne.g., [http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/12100 January 23, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125192804/http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/12100 |date=January 25, 2012 }} \n</ref> [[ABC News]],<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/video/york-times-nate-silver-top-line-11746871 ABC \"Topline\", 9\u201328, 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101025234919/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/video/york-times-nate-silver-top-line-11746871 |date=October 25, 2010 }}.</ref> and [[Current TV]].<ref>\nFor example, on Keith Olbermann's [http://current.com/shows/countdown/videos/nate-silver-discusses-romneys-woes-in-michigan-and-nationwide \"Countdown\" on February 14, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215150820/http://current.com/shows/countdown/videos/nate-silver-discusses-romneys-woes-in-michigan-and-nationwide |date=February 15, 2012 }}\n</ref>\n\nSilver also appeared on ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' (October 7, 2008 and November 5, 2012),<ref>[http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/187343/october-07-2008/nate-silver Nate Silver on \"Colbert Report\" 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218221050/http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/187343/october-07-2008/nate-silver |date=December 18, 2008 }} and [http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/420765/november-05-2012/nate-silver Nate Silver on \"Colbert Report\" 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106131448/http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/420765/november-05-2012/nate-silver |date=November 6, 2012 }}.</ref> ''[[The Daily Show]]'' (October 17, 2012 and November 7, 2012),<ref>[http://www.thedailyshow.com/full-episodes/wed-october-17-2012-nate-silver Nate Silver on \"The Daily Show\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018204825/http://www.thedailyshow.com/full-episodes/wed-october-17-2012-nate-silver |date=October 18, 2012 }}.</ref> and ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'' (October 26, 2012).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hbo.com/real-time-with-bill-maher/episodes/index.html#/real-time-with-bill-maher/episodes/0/264-episode/index.html |title=Real Time with Bill Maher |publisher=Hbo.com |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214053343/http://www.hbo.com/real-time-with-bill-maher/episodes/index.html#/real-time-with-bill-maher/episodes/0/264-episode/index.html |archive-date=December 14, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThat Silver accurately predicted the outcome of the 2012 presidential race, in the face of numerous public attacks on his forecasts by critics, inspired many articles in the press, ranging from [[Gizmodo]],<ref>Nick Stango, \"[https://gizmodo.com/5958549/top-25-nate-silver-facts Top 25 Nate Silver Facts] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801235117/http://gizmodo.com/5958549/top-25-nate-silver-facts |date=August 1, 2017 }}\", [[Gizmodo]], November 7, 2012.</ref> to online and mainstream newspapers,<ref>Chris Taylor, \"[http://mashable.com/2012/11/07/nate-silver-wins/ The Triumph of the Nerds] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108050813/http://mashable.com/2012/11/07/nate-silver-wins/ |date=November 8, 2012 }}\", [[Mashable]], November 7, 2012]; Jocelyn Noveck, \"He called it, and now Silver's a pop-culture star\", [http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_ELECTION_THE_OTHER_WINNER Associated Press, November 9, 2012]; Martin Robbins, \"Can Nate Silver's example save political journalism?\" ''[[The Guardian]]'', November 13, 2012; Ken Bensinger, \"[http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-fi-election-math-20121108,0,2926239.story Number crunchers were right about Obama despite what pundits said] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111064637/http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-fi-election-math-20121108,0,2926239.story |date=November 11, 2012 }}\", [[Los Angeles Times]], November 8, 2012; James Rainey, \"[http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-nate-silver-polls-rasmussen-20121107,0,3329768.story Parsing polls: Nate Silver picks on target, Rasmussen not so much] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109120837/http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-nate-silver-polls-rasmussen-20121107,0,3329768.story |date=November 9, 2012 }}\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]],'' November 8, 2012; Ron Seely, \"[http://host.madison.com/news/science/seely-on-science-nate-silver-gains-fame-by-harnessing-power/article_cf087458-29f8-11e2-a2d4-001a4bcf887a.html?comment_form=true#comments Seely on Science: Nate Silver gains fame by harnessing power of math] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623061821/https://host.madison.com/news/science/seely-on-science-nate-silver-gains-fame-by-harnessing-power/article_cf087458-29f8-11e2-a2d4-001a4bcf887a.html?comment_form=true#comments |date=June 23, 2018 }}\", [[Wisconsin State Journal]], November 9, 2012; Greg Sargent, \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/post/what-nate-silver-really-accomplished/2012/11/21/6f9f10c2-3410-11e2-bfd5-e202b6d7b501_blog.html What Nate Silver Really Accomplished] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802083350/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/post/what-nate-silver-really-accomplished/2012/11/21/6f9f10c2-3410-11e2-bfd5-e202b6d7b501_blog.html |date=August 2, 2017 }}\", ''The Washington Post'', November 21, 2012; Aluf Benn, \"After 2012, make way for the digital press\", ''[[Haaretz]],'' December 29, 2012.</ref> news and commentary magazines,<ref>Conor Friedersdorf, \"How Conservative Media Lost to the MSM and Failed the Rank and File\", ''[[The Atlantic]]'', [https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/11/how-conservative-media-lost-to-the-msm-and-failed-the-rank-and-file/264855/ November 7, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120192322/http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/11/how-conservative-media-lost-to-the-msm-and-failed-the-rank-and-file/264855/ |date=January 20, 2017 }}; Frank Rich, \"Fantasyland: Denial has poisoned the GOP and threatens the rest of the country too\", ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]],'' [http://nymag.com/news/frank-rich/gop-denial-2012-11/ November 9, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112032739/http://nymag.com/news/frank-rich/gop-denial-2012-11/ |date=November 12, 2012 }}.</ref> business media,<ref>Tarun Wadhwa, \"Nate Silver and the Rise of Political Data Science\",  ''[[Forbes]],'' [https://www.forbes.com/sites/singularity/2012/11/07/nate-silver-and-the-rise-of-political-data-science/ November 7, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802092627/https://www.forbes.com/sites/singularity/2012/11/07/nate-silver-and-the-rise-of-political-data-science/ |date=August 2, 2017 }}; Dorie Clark, \"How Nate Silver Won the 2012 Presidential Election\",  ''[[Harvard Business Review]],'' [http://blogs.hbr.org/cs/2012/11/how_nate_silver_won_the_2012_p.html November 7, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111083605/http://blogs.hbr.org/cs/2012/11/how_nate_silver_won_the_2012_p.html |date=November 11, 2012 }}; Steve LeVine, \"The smart guesswork that applies even in Nate Silver's world\", ''Quartz,'' [http://qz.com/25855/the-smart-guesswork-that-applies-even-in-nate-silvers-world/ November 11, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113205926/http://qz.com/25855/the-smart-guesswork-that-applies-even-in-nate-silvers-world/ |date=November 13, 2012 }}; Joe Weisenthal, \"Here's The Real Reason Nate Silver's Perfect Election Call Was Such An Awesome Breakthrough\", [[Business Insider]], [http://www.businessinsider.com/nate-silver-and-the-end-of-ex-post-facto-excuses-2012-11 November 10, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110233614/http://www.businessinsider.com/nate-silver-and-the-end-of-ex-post-facto-excuses-2012-11 |date=November 10, 2012 }}; Irving Wladawsky-Berger, \"Nate Silver, FiveThirtyEight Prove Predictive Analytics Getting Real\", ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [https://blogs.wsj.com/cio/2012/12/16/nate-silver-fivethirtyeight-prove-predictive-analytics-getting-real/ December 16, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623033333/https://blogs.wsj.com/cio/2012/12/16/nate-silver-fivethirtyeight-prove-predictive-analytics-getting-real/ |date=June 23, 2018 }}.</ref> trade journals,<ref>Eric Lundquist, \"Nate Silver's Big Data Lessons For The Enterprise\", ''[[Information Week]]'', [http://www.informationweek.com/global-cio/interviews/nate-silvers-big-data-lessons-for-the-en/240062638 November 8, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110192706/http://www.informationweek.com/global-cio/interviews/nate-silvers-big-data-lessons-for-the-en/240062638 |date=November 10, 2012 }}; Daniel Terdiman, \"Among the top election quants, Nate Silver reigns supreme\", ''[[CNET]],'' [http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-57546778-38/among-the-top-election-quants-nate-silver-reigns-supreme/ November 8, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108150326/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-57546778-38/among-the-top-election-quants-nate-silver-reigns-supreme/ |date=November 8, 2012 }}.</ref> media about media,<ref>Kelly McBride, \"What Nate Silver's success says about the 4th and 5th estates\", ''[[Poynter Institute|Poynter]],'' [http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/making-sense-of-news/194843/what-nate-silvers-success-says-about-the-4th-and-5th-estates/ November 8, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110203932/http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/making-sense-of-news/194843/what-nate-silvers-success-says-about-the-4th-and-5th-estates/ |date=November 10, 2012 }} ; Jonathan Stray, \"Data, uncertainty, and specialization: What journalism can learn from FiveThirtyEight's election coverage\", ''Nieman Journalism Lab,'' [http://www.niemanlab.org/2012/10/data-uncertainty-and-specialization-what-journalism-can-learn-from-fivethirtyeights-election-coverage/ October 31, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107042925/http://www.niemanlab.org/2012/10/data-uncertainty-and-specialization-what-journalism-can-learn-from-fivethirtyeights-election-coverage/ |date=November 7, 2012 }}.</ref> and ''[[Scientific American]]'',<ref>Jennifer Ouellette, \"Why Math is Like the Honey Badger: Nate Silver\", ''Scientific American,'' [http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/cocktail-party-physics/2012/11/07/why-math-is-like-the-honey-badger-nate-silver-ascendant November 7, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108123907/http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/cocktail-party-physics/2012/11/07/why-math-is-like-the-honey-badger-nate-silver-ascendant/ |date=November 8, 2012 }}; and Bora Zivkovic, \"Nate Silver and the Ascendance of Expertise\", ''Scientific American,'' [http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/a-blog-around-the-clock/2012/11/14/nate-silver-and-the-ascendance-of-expertise/ November 14, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117094143/http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/a-blog-around-the-clock/2012/11/14/nate-silver-and-the-ascendance-of-expertise/ |date=November 17, 2012 }}.</ref> as well as a feature interview on ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|The Today Show]]'',<ref>\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20121111134653/http://video.today.msnbc.msn.com/today/49757709#49757709 Today Show]  , November 9, 2012.\n</ref> a return appearance on ''[[The Daily Show]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/wed-november-7-2012/nate-silver |title=Silver on Daily Show, Nov. 7, 2012 |publisher=Thedailyshow.com |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231190840/http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/wed-november-7-2012/nate-silver |archive-date=December 31, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> and an appearance on ''[[Morning Joe]]''<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3036789/ns/msnbc-morning_joe/#49899665 ''Morning Joe''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127214344/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3036789/ns/msnbc-morning_joe/#49899665 |date=January 27, 2013 }} on November 20, 2012.</ref>\n\nSilver's first appearance on [[ABC News]] as Editor-in-Chief of the new ''FiveThirtyEight.com'' was on [[George Stephanopoulos]]'s ''[[This Week (ABC TV series)|This Week]]'' on November 3, 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/ThisWeek/video/espns-nate-silver-week-2014-election-picture-20770078 |title=ABC News \"This Week\" |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209192705/http://abcnews.go.com/ThisWeek/video/espns-nate-silver-week-2014-election-picture-20770078 |archive-date=December 9, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSilver is referenced in the [[Syfy channel]] show ''[[The Magicians (U.S. TV series)|The Magicians]]'' as an earth wizard who uses polling spells.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/go/263294|title=The Magicians Season 2 Episode 10 Review: The Girl Who Told Time|website=Den of Geek}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Silver appeared on the podcast ''[[Employee of the Month (podcast)|Employee of the Month]]'', where he criticized [[Vox Media]] for \"recycling Wikipedia entries\" in their content.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/11/09/nate-silver-accuses-vox-of-recycling-wikipedia-entries/|title=Nate Silver accuses Vox of recycling Wikipedia entries|last=Wemple|first=Erik|date=2015-11-09|website=The Washington Post|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition and awards==\n* In September 2008, ''FiveThirtyEight'' became the first blog ever selected as a Notable Narrative by the [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]] at [[Harvard University]].<ref>\"FiveThirtyEight.com earns the distinction of being the first blog selected as a Notable Narrative. In his posts, former economic analyst and baseball-stats wunderkind Nate Silver explains the presidential race, using the dramatic tension inherent in the run-up to Election Day to drive his narrative....\" See [http://www.niemanstoryboard.org/?s=fivethirtyeight&cat=317 ''Nieman Storyboard''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115174502/http://www.niemanstoryboard.org/?s=fivethirtyeight&cat=317 |date=January 15, 2013 }}. [Retrieved July 12, 2012].</ref>\n* November 2008: [[Crain Communications Inc.|Crain's Chicago Business]] profiled Silver as one of Chicago's \"40 under 40\" notable young entrepreneurs.<ref>Mike Colias, [http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/mag/article.pl?articleId=30886 \"Nate Silver\", ''Chicago Business'', November 3, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081107053459/http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/mag/article.pl?articleId=30886 |date=November 7, 2008 }}. For a video interview related to this profile, see [http://link.brightcove.com/services/player/bcpid1274025952?bclid=1285255975&bctid=31289715001 Nate Silver, FiveThirtyEight.com] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603145303/http://link.brightcove.com/services/player/bcpid1274025952?bclid=1285255975&bctid=31289715001 |date=June 3, 2012 }}.</ref>\n* November 9, 2008: ''[[The New York Times]]'' called Silver \"perhaps the most unlikely media star to emerge\" out of \"an election season of unlikely outcomes\" and described ''FiveThirtyEight'' with its almost five million page views on Election Day as \"one of the breakout online stars of the year\".<ref name=\"2008-11-09\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/10/business/media/10silver.html|title=Finding Fame With a Prescient Call for Obama|publisher=[[nytimes.com]]|accessdate=November 10, 2008|first=Stephanie|last=Clifford|date=November 10, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224063509/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/10/business/media/10silver.html|archive-date=February 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* December 2008: ''[[Newsweek|Newsweek.com]]'' identified Silver's November 3, 2008 article \"What to Watch For \u2013 An hour-by-hour guide to election night\"<ref>Nate Silver, \"What to Watch For \u2013 An hour-by-hour guide to election night\", [http://www.newsweek.com/id/167186 Newsweek.com, November 3, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231063845/http://www.newsweek.com/id/167186 |date=December 31, 2008 }}.</ref> as the 4th most viewed story on Newsweek.com in 2008.<ref>Year in Review: Murder, Politics And Crocs \u2013 The top 10 most viewed stories on Newsweek.com in 2008\", [http://www.newsweek.com/id/176822 ''Newsweek.com,'' December 23, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227043557/http://www.newsweek.com/id/176822 |date=December 27, 2008 }}.</ref>\n* December 2008: named by ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' as one of the \"Breakout Stars of 2008\".<ref>[http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2008-12-31/breakout-stars-of-2008/#gallery=102;page=6 ''The Daily Beast'', December 21, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101120211/http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2008-12-31/breakout-stars-of-2008/#gallery=102;page=6 |date=January 1, 2009 }}.</ref>\n* February 2009: named by [[James Wolcott]] in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' as one of the \"Winners of 2008\": \"No shiny arrow shot swifter and loftier from obscurity to quotable authority than Nate Silver, whose FiveThirtyEight.com site became the expert sensation of the election season ...<ref>James Wolcott, \"The Good, the Bad, and Joe Lieberman\", [http://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/02/wolcott200902 ''VanityFair.com,'' February 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101102422/http://www.vanityfair.com./politics/features/2009/02/wolcott200902 |date=January 1, 2009 }}.</ref>\n* January 2009: Silver was named by ''[[Forbes.com]]'' to its third annual \"Web Celeb 25\", which \"track[s] the biggest and brightest stars on the Web, the people who have turned their passions into new-media empires\".<ref>\"The Web Celeb 25\", [https://www.forbes.com/2009/01/29/web-celebrities-internet-technology-webceleb09_0129_land.html ''[[Forbes.com]]'', January 29, 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918105248/http://www.forbes.com/2009/01/29/web-celebrities-internet-technology-webceleb09_0129_land.html |date=September 18, 2012 }}.</ref>\n* April 2009: Silver was named as one of the \"Rolling Stone 100: Agents of Change\".<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/26754176/the_rs_100_agents_of_change/2 ''Rolling Stone'', April 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329062220/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/26754176/the_rs_100_agents_of_change/2 |date=March 29, 2010 }}.</ref>\n* April 27, 2009: named \"Blogger of the Year\" by ''[[The Week]]'' in its 6th annual Opinion Awards.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.theweek.com/opinionawards/winners.html |title=The Week Opinion Awards |magazine=[[The Week]] |accessdate=May 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110083746/http://www.theweek.com/opinionawards/winners.html |archivedate=January 10, 2010 }}</ref>\n* April 30, 2009: Silver was named one of [[Time 100|\"The World's 100 Most Influential People\"]] by ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"specials1\"/>\n* December 2009: Silver was recognized by ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' in its \"Ninth Annual Year in Ideas\" article for his \"Forensic Polling Analysis\" of the possible falsification of data by a polling firm.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/projects/magazine/ideas/2009 ''New York Times Magazine'' \"Forensic Polling Analysis\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207232047/http://www.nytimes.com/projects/magazine/ideas/2009/ |date=February 7, 2017 }}.</ref>\n* 2009: named \"Speaker of the Year\" by the intercollegiate [[Cross Examination Debate Association]] (CEDA).<ref>{{cite web|author=CEDA Awards|url=http://awards.cedadebate.org/|title=CEDA Awards|publisher=Awards.cedadebate.org|accessdate=August 21, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414122459/http://awards.cedadebate.org/|archivedate=April 14, 2012}}</ref>\n* November 2010: [[John F. Harris]], Editor-in-Chief of ''[[Politico.com|Politico]]'' writing in ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine, listed Nate Silver as one of seven bloggers among \"The Most Powerful People on Earth\".<ref>John F. Harris, \"The Most Powerful People On Earth: My Picks: Bloggers\", ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine, November 22, 2010 [https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/1122/powerful-people-10-john-harris-chait-hot-air-my-picks-bloggers.html (retrieved online at Forbes.com)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113030217/http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/1122/powerful-people-10-john-harris-chait-hot-air-my-picks-bloggers.html |date=November 13, 2010 }}.</ref>\n*In December 2010: ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' magazine included Silver on its list of the top 100 [[LGBT]] people of the year.<ref>{{cite news|title=16th Annual Out100|url=http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/out100/2010/11/11/16th-annual-out100#slide-32|accessdate=October 27, 2012|newspaper=OUT Magazine|date=December 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020141921/http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/out100/2010/11/11/16th-annual-out100#slide-32|archive-date=October 20, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* May 2011: Presented the [[Henry F. Pringle|Henry Pringle Lecture]] at the [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism|Columbia Journalism School]].<ref>Jim Romenesko, \"Silver's advice to young journalists in the digital age\", ''[[Poynter Institute|Poynter]],'' May 23, 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.columbia.edu/system/documents/477/original/nate_silver.pdf|title=Text of Henry Pringle Lecture, 2011|format=PDF|date=May 17, 2011|accessdate=August 21, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626013124/http://www.journalism.columbia.edu/system/documents/477/original/nate_silver.pdf|archivedate=June 26, 2011}}</ref>\n* March 2012: [[Crain Communications, Inc.|Crain's New York Business]] featured Silver as one of New York City's \"Forty Under Forty\" notable young entrepreneurs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mycrains.crainsnewyork.com/40under40/profiles/2012/nate-silver|title=Crain's New York|publisher=Mycrains.crainsnewyork.com|date=March 24, 2012|accessdate=August 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809073000/http://mycrains.crainsnewyork.com/40under40/profiles/2012/nate-silver|archive-date=August 9, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* May 2012: ''FiveThirtyEight'' won a [[Webby Award]] for \"Best Political Blog\" from the [[International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences]] in the 16th annual Webby Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current.php?season=16 |title=2012 Webby winner |publisher=Webbyawards.com |accessdate=August 21, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820093559/http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current.php?season=16 |archivedate=August 20, 2012  }}</ref>\n* December 2012: ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named Silver one of its Game Changers in 2012.<ref>\"Nate Silver: Scourge of the Pundits\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', December 12, 2012, p. 66.</ref>\n* December 2012: ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' named Silver as Person of the Year.<ref>Aaron Hicklin, \"Nate Silver: Person of the Year\", ''Out'', [http://www.out.com/news-opinion/2012/12/18/nate-silver-person-year December 18, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219224130/http://www.out.com/news-opinion/2012/12/18/nate-silver-person-year |date=December 19, 2012 }}.</ref>\n* December 2012: Named by ''Washington Post'' columnist [[Chris Cillizza]] as having the \"Best Year in Washington in 2012\" among the \"winners and losers of 2012\".<ref>\"Best year in Washington: Nate Silver\", ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/best-year-in-washington-nate-silver/2012/12/28/25787838-4dee-11e2-950a-7863a013264b_story.html December 29, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802050507/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/best-year-in-washington-nate-silver/2012/12/28/25787838-4dee-11e2-950a-7863a013264b_story.html |date=August 2, 2017 }}.</ref>\n* April 2013: ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' ranked Silver No. 6 on its \"Power List 50\", the \"7th annual ranked list of the gay men and women whose power and prestige is instrumental in influencing the way Americans think about, and engage with, the world\".<ref>[http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/power-50/2013/04/10/power-list-2013 \"2013 Power List\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413110518/http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/power-50/2013/04/10/power-list-2013 |date=April 13, 2013 }},  ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]''.</ref>\n* April 2013: ''FiveThirtyEight'' won a Webby Award for \"Best Political Blog\" from the International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences in the 17th annual Webby Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://winners.webbyawards.com/2013/web/general-website/blog-political |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412023128/http://winners.webbyawards.com/2013/web/general-website/blog-political |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 12, 2013 |title=17th Annual Webby Awards, \"Best Political Blog\" |publisher=Winners.webbyawards.com |accessdate=December 5, 2013 }}</ref>\n* May 2013: Silver was named by [[Fast Company (magazine)|''Fast Company'']] as No. 1 of its \"100 Most Creative People in Business 2013\".<ref>\"!00 Most Creative People in Business 2013\", [[Fast Company (magazine)|''Fast Company'']], [http://www.fastcompany.com/section/most-creative-people-2013 May 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516043256/http://www.fastcompany.com/section/most-creative-people-2013 |date=May 16, 2013 }}; and Jon Gertner, \"The Data Demystifier\", [[Fast Company (magazine)|''Fast Company'']], [http://www.fastcompany.com/3009258/most-creative-people-2013/1-nate-silver May 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516043404/http://www.fastcompany.com/3009258/most-creative-people-2013/1-nate-silver |date=May 16, 2013 }}.</ref>\n* May 12, 2013: Silver received an honorary [[Doctor of Science]] degree (''Scienti\u00e6 Doctor honoris causa'' \u2013 D.Sc. h.c.) and gave the commencement address at [[Ripon College (Wisconsin)|Ripon College]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E6GAKeFh8SE Ripon 2013 video] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504010456/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E6GAKeFh8SE |date=May 4, 2016 }} of Ripon College honorary degree award and commencement speech.</ref>\n* May 24, 2013: Silver received an honorary [[Doctor of Letters|Doctor of Literature]] degree (Doctor of Literature ''honoris causa'') and presented a commencement address at [[The New School]].<ref>[http://vimeo.com/67336820 New School 2013 commencement video] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203104703/http://vimeo.com/67336820 |date=February 3, 2014 }}.</ref>\n* June 2013: The University of Chicago granted Silver a \"Professional Achievement Award\" at its 72nd annual Alumni Awards Ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alumniandfriends.uchicago.edu/site/c.mjJXJ7MLIsE/b.8302249/k.6FEE/2013_Alumni_Awards.htm|title=Past Award Winners|work=Alumni Association: Alumni, Parents, Families & Friends|access-date=January 19, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228202601/http://alumniandfriends.uchicago.edu/site/c.mjJXJ7MLIsE/b.8302249/k.6FEE/2013_Alumni_Awards.htm|archive-date=February 28, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* June 2013: The [[S.I. Newhouse School of Public Communications]] at [[Syracuse University]] gave Silver the \"i3 award for impact, innovation and influence\" at its 13th annual Mirror Awards ceremony.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mirrorawards.syr.edu/2013/06/05/newhouse-school-announces-winners-in-2013-mirror-awards-competition/ |title=Newhouse \"Mirror Awards\" |publisher=Mirrorawards.syr.edu |date=June 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613162527/http://mirrorawards.syr.edu/2013/06/05/newhouse-school-announces-winners-in-2013-mirror-awards-competition/ |archive-date=June 13, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* August 2013: Presented the President's Invited Address at the [[Joint Statistical Meetings]] in Montreal, Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amstat.org/meetings/jsm/2013/index.cfm |title=Joint Statistical Meetings 2013 |publisher=Amstat.org |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830111426/https://www.amstat.org/meetings/jsm/2013/index.cfm |archive-date=August 30, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>For an interview conducted at this meeting, see \"Nate Silver: What I Need from Statisticians\", ''Statistics Views,'' [http://www.statisticsviews.com/details/feature/5133141/Nate-Silver-What-I-need-from-statisticians.html August 23, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823091106/http://www.statisticsviews.com/details/feature/5133141/Nate-Silver-What-I-need-from-statisticians.html |date=August 23, 2013 }}.</ref>\n* October 2013: Silver's ''The Signal and the Noise'' won the 2013 [[Phi Beta Kappa Award in Science]], which recognizes \"outstanding contributions by scientists to the literature of science\".<ref name=\"pbk.org\"/>\n* December 2013: The [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven|University of Leuven (KU Leuven)]] (Belgium) and the Leuven Statistics Research Centre awarded Silver an honorary doctoral degree \"for his prominent role in the development, application, and dissemination of proper prediction methods in sports and in political sciences\".<ref>\n\"Honorary Doctorate for Nate Silver\", [http://lstat.kuleuven.be/LStat25/Nate%20Silver.htm LStat: Leuven Statistics Research Centre] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20131204045244/http://lstat.kuleuven.be/LStat25/Nate%20Silver.htm |date=December 4, 2013 }} \n</ref><ref>\nLuc Vander Elst, \"Honorary doctorate for Nate Silver, the man who made statistics cool\", KU Leuven, [http://www.kuleuven.be/english/news/honorary-doctorate-for-nate-silver-the-man-who-made-statistics-cool December 18, 2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224103042/http://www.kuleuven.be/english/news/honorary-doctorate-for-nate-silver-the-man-who-made-statistics-cool |date=December 24, 2013 }} \n</ref>\n* January 2014: Silver was named to ''[[Advertising Age]]'s'' \"40 Under 40\" list of \"the Bright Young Stars of Marketing\".<ref>\"Meet Ad Age's 40 Under 40\", [http://adage.com/article/news/meet-ad-age-s-40-40/290948/#Silver January 20, 2014] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221105027/http://adage.com/article/news/meet-ad-age-s-40-40/290948/#Silver |date=February 21, 2014 }}.</ref>\n* May 25, 2014: Silver received a Doctorate of Humane Letters, ''honoris causa'', from [[Amherst College]].<ref>Honorary doctorate from Amherst, [https://www.amherst.edu/aboutamherst/news/specialevents/commencement/awards/2014-honorees/nate-silver 2014] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220605/https://www.amherst.edu/aboutamherst/news/specialevents/commencement/awards/2014-honorees/nate-silver |date=May 27, 2014 }}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://photos.masslive.com/republican/2014/05/193rd_commencement_at_amherst_college_18.html|title=193rd Commencement at Amherst College|work=masslive.com|access-date=May 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527215510/http://photos.masslive.com/republican/2014/05/193rd_commencement_at_amherst_college_18.html|archive-date=May 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*May 2015: Silver won the [[Warren Mitofsky|Warren J. Mitofsky]] Innovators Award from the [[American Association for Public Opinion Research]] (AAPOR) \"for Contributions to the General Public and Mass Media in the Realm of Statistical Literacy and Thinking\".<ref>AAPOR Award {{cite web |url=http://www.aapor.org/AAPORKentico/Awards/Awards.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 18, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518093554/http://www.aapor.org/AAPORKentico/Awards/Awards.aspx |archivedate=May 18, 2015  }}. The citation read: \"2015 Warren J. Mitofsky Innovators Award to Nate Silver for Contributions to the General Public and Mass Media in the Realm of Statistical Literacy and Thinking. Through his work as Founding Director and Editor in Chief of FiveThirtyEight.com Nate Silver has made significant, innovative contributions to how journalists report and the general public understands presidential and congressional elections in the United States, and how public opinion polling is used in that framework. Silver's focus on the Electoral College, rather than the popular vote, has fundamentally reshaped how presidential elections are reported, leading to a greater public and journalistic awareness of how the electoral political process operates. Silver's application of probability theory and statistical inference to politics, public policy, economics, and daily life in FiveThirtyEight.com has advanced and highlighted statistical literacy and thinking as an approach to solving problems in a number of areas. One example is in the use of polling aggregation to identify central tendencies and outliers in the analysis of elections. AAPOR also recognizes and laud's Silver's commitment to transparency and full disclosure in FiveThirtyEight's research methods and practice. These principles remain the bedrock on which scientific inquiry is grounded\".</ref>\n*October 2016: Silver was honored by the National [[Museum of Mathematics]] at its \"Race to the Finish: MoMath's Annual Gala\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://momath.org/civicrm/?page=CiviCRM&q=civicrm/event/info&reset=1&id=673&noheader=1|title=Race to the Finish: MoMath's annual gala honoring Nate Silver - National Museum of MathematicsNational Museum of Mathematics|first1=Guastavino's 409 East 59th Street New|last1=York|first2=NY 10022 United|last2=States|access-date=August 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227120843/https://momath.org/civicrm/?page=CiviCRM&q=civicrm%2Fevent%2Finfo&reset=1&id=673&noheader=1|archive-date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*May 2017: Georgetown University awarded Silver a degree of Doctor of Humane Letters ''honoris causa''.<ref>[https://www.georgetown.edu/news/commencement-speakers-2017 \"Georgetown Announces 2017 Commencement Speakers\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517070642/https://www.georgetown.edu/news/commencement-speakers-2017 |date=May 17, 2017 }}.</ref>\n*May 2018: Kenyon College awarded Silver a degree, Doctor of Humane Letters.<ref>[http://www.kenyon.edu/middle-path/for-the-media/media-relations/press-release-archives/kenyon-set-to-celebrate-190th-commencement-fivethirtyeight-editor-nate-silver-to-give-address/ Kenyon College honorary degree] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180520054900/http://www.kenyon.edu/middle-path/for-the-media/media-relations/press-release-archives/kenyon-set-to-celebrate-190th-commencement-fivethirtyeight-editor-nate-silver-to-give-address/ |date=May 20, 2018 }}.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn a 2012 interview with [[Charlie Rose]] he stated, \"I'd say I am somewhere in between being a [[libertarian]] and a [[liberalism|liberal]]. So if I were to vote it would be kind of a [[Gary Johnson]] versus [[Mitt Romney]] decision, I suppose.\"<ref>{{cite episode |title=Mark Halperin of Time magazine and Nate Silver of FiveThirtyEight.com on the Presidential election |url=http://www.charlierose.com/watch/60140283 |series=[[Charlie Rose (TV series)|Charlie Rose]] |first=Charlie (host) |last=Rose |network=[[PBS]] |date=October 29, 2012 |accessdate=October 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926073817/http://charlierose.com/watch/60140283 |archivedate=September 26, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nSilver is a grandnephew of geologists [[Caswell Silver]] and [[Leon Silver]]. He is a great grandson of Harmon Lewis, the President of Alcoa Steamship Company,<ref>See comments to [http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/Interfaith_Celebrities_Nate_Silver_Another_Bond_and_Happy_Endings.shtml Interfaith Families, Nov. 13, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121121022651/http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/Interfaith_Celebrities_Nate_Silver_Another_Bond_and_Happy_Endings.shtml |date=November 21, 2012 }} by Nate Bloom [retrieved December 1, 2012]</ref> as well as a great great nephew of the embryologist [[Warren Harmon Lewis]] and his wife, biologist [[Margaret Reed Lewis]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nSilver is [[openly gay]].<ref>Carole Cadwalladr, \"Nate Silver: it's the numbers, stupid\", [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/nov/17/nate-silver-interview-election-data-statistics/ ''[[The Guardian]],'' November 17, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121173702/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/nov/17/nate-silver-interview-election-data-statistics |date=November 21, 2016 }}.</ref> \"I've always felt like something of an outsider. I've always had friends, but I've always come from an outside point of view. I think that's important. If you grow up gay, or in a household that's agnostic, when most people are religious, then from the get-go, you are saying that there are things that the majority of society believes that I don't believe\", he told an interviewer in 2012.<ref name=\"guardian1\">Carole Cadwalladr, \"Nate Silver: it's the numbers, stupid\", [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/nov/17/nate-silver-interview-election-data-statistics/ ''[[The Observer]],'' November 17, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121173702/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/nov/17/nate-silver-interview-election-data-statistics |date=November 21, 2016 }}.</ref> \"When asked what made you feel more of a misfit, being gay or being a geek, he replied, 'Probably the numbers stuff since I had that from when I was six.'\"<ref name=\"guardian1\"/> When asked in 2008 if he had noticed people looking at him as a \"gay icon\", he responded, \"I've started to notice it a little bit, although so far it seems like I'm more a subject of geek affection than gay affection\".<ref>Japhy Grant, \"Nate Silver on African-Americans, Prop 8. and Being A Hero to Gays & Geeks Everywhere\", [http://www.queerty.com/exclusive-nate-silver-on-african-americans-prop-8-and-being-a-hero-to-gays-geeks-everywhere-20081121/ ''Queerty'', November 21, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115151157/http://www.queerty.com/exclusive-nate-silver-on-african-americans-prop-8-and-being-a-hero-to-gays-geeks-everywhere-20081121/ |date=November 15, 2012 }}. [retrieved November 6, 2012]</ref>\n\nSilver discussed his sexuality in the context of growing up in East Lansing, in an article about the [[U.S. Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] ruling ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' in favor of recognizing [[same-sex marriage]] on the date of its announcement. He analyzed the speed of the change of public sentiment, pointing out that the change over only several decades has been palpable to the current generations.<ref name=\"2015-06-26_Silver\">[http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/change-doesnt-usually-come-this-fast/ Change Doesn't Usually Come This Fast] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150628221311/http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/change-doesnt-usually-come-this-fast/ |date=June 28, 2015 }}, Nate Silver, ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'', June 26, 2015, accessed June 29, 2015</ref>\n\nSilver has long been interested in [[fantasy baseball]], especially Scoresheet Baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scoresheet.com/BB_index.php|title=Scoresheet Fantasy Baseball Overview &#124; The best fantasy baseball sim game|website=www.scoresheet.com|access-date=July 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170726220203/http://www.scoresheet.com/BB_index.php|archive-date=July 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> While in college he served as an expert on Scoresheet Baseball for [[Ron Shandler|BaseballHQ]].<ref>Zak Stambor, \"Number Cruncher\", [http://magazine.uchicago.edu/0878/features/nate_silver.shtml ''University of Chicago Magazine'', July\u2013August, 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080721011512/http://magazine.uchicago.edu/0878/features/nate_silver.shtml |date=July 21, 2008 }}.</ref> When he took up political writing, Silver abandoned his blog, ''The Burrito Bracket'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burritobracket.blogspot.com/|title=BurritoBracket.com|publisher=Burritobracket.blogspot.com|date=February 23, 2004|accessdate=August 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130114195034/http://burritobracket.blogspot.com/|archive-date=January 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> in which he ran a one-and-done competition among the taquerias in his [[Wicker Park, Chicago|Wicker Park]] neighborhood in Chicago.<ref>On the role of ''The Burrito Bracket'' in Silver's engagement in blogging see Dan Cohen, \"The Ivory Tower and the Open Web: Introduction: Burritos, Browsers, and Books\", [http://www.dancohen.org/2011/07/26/the-ivory-tower-and-the-open-web-introduction-burritos-browsers-and-books-draft/ Dan Cohen's ''Digital Humanities'' blog, July 26, 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810001104/http://www.dancohen.org/2011/07/26/the-ivory-tower-and-the-open-web-introduction-burritos-browsers-and-books-draft/ |date=August 10, 2011 }}. [retrieved August 6, 2011]</ref>\n\nSilver plays [[poker]] semi-professionally.<ref>See Hageman, cited previously; {{cite news|title=Players Place Bets on Poker as Career|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-10-03/business/0410030372_1_online-poker-poker-sites-interest-in-online-gaming|publisher=Chicago Tribune|last=Kaiser|first=Rob|date=October 3, 2004|accessdate=July 2, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115164158/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-10-03/business/0410030372_1_online-poker-poker-sites-interest-in-online-gaming|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=This Post Brought to You by Poker|url=http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2009/07/this-post-brought-to-you-by-poker.html|publisher=FiveThirtyEight.com|last=Silver|first=Nate|date=July 2, 2009|accessdate=November 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126021614/http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2009/07/this-post-brought-to-you-by-poker.html|archive-date=November 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball|Politics|Mathematics|Journalism|Biography|LGBT}}\n* [[Computational statistics]]\n* [[Editorial board]]\n* [[LGBT culture in New York City]]\n* [[List of self-identified LGBTQ New Yorkers]]\n* [[New Yorkers in journalism]]\n* [[Political analysis]]\n* [[Sports betting]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Calderone |first1=Michael |title=Behind Nate Silver\u2019s war with The New York Times |work=[[Politico]] |date=2019-08-15 |url=https://politi.co/2OZp0dw |language=en |accessdate=2019-08-18 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{C-SPAN|natesilver}}\n* Appearances in the [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3156370/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1 Internet Movie Database]\n* Interviews, appearances, presentations available on [https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=nate+silver YouTube].\n* [http://bloggingheads.tv/diavlogs/13822 Silver discussing his methodology for polling aggregation] on [[Bloggingheads.tv]] (August 21, 2008) [video]\n* [http://www.ted.com/index.php/talks/nate_silver_on_race_and_politics.html TED 2009 talk about race and the 2008 U.S. presidential election] (February 2009) [video]\n* Archive of ''Esquire'' [https://archive.today/20120729061021/http://www.esquire.com/archive/features/data/0/10/ \"The Data\" series of articles, 2008-9]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mYIgSq-ZWE0 ''The Signal and the Noise'' \"Authors at Google\" talk] (November 26, 2012) [video]\n* [http://teamcoco.com/video/nate-silver-serious-jibber-jabber \"Serious Jibber-Jabber with Conan O'Brien\"] (December 7, 2012) [video]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141213005104/http://techtv.mit.edu/collections/comm-forum/videos/23071-a-conversation-with-nate-silver-mit-communications-forum \"A Conversation with Nate Silver\"] at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] Communications Forum, ([[Seth Mnookin]], interviewer) (February 28, 2013) [video]\n* [http://www.statisticsviews.com/details/feature/5133141/Nate-Silver-What-I-need-from-statisticians.html Video interview about his career] in statistics at [[Joint Statistical Meeting]], August 5, 2013\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141209215842/http://podcast.baseballprospectus.com/podcast/EffectivelyWildEpisode538.mp3 Interview] on [[Baseball Prospectus]] podcast \"Effective